'''The Beach Boys''' are an American [[Rock music|rock]] band formed in [[Hawthorne, California]] in 1961. The group's [[The Beach Boys lineups|original lineup]] consisted of brothers [[Brian Wilson|Brian]], [[Dennis Wilson|Dennis]], and [[Carl Wilson]], their cousin [[Mike Love]], and their friend [[Al Jardine]]. They emerged at the vanguard of the "[[California Sound]]", initially performing original [[surf music|surf songs]] that gained international popularity for their distinct [[vocal harmony|vocal harmonies]] and lyrics reflecting a [[southern California]] [[youth culture]] of [[surfing]], cars, and romance. Rooted in [[jazz]]-based [[vocal music|vocal groups]], 1950s [[rock and roll]], and [[doo-wop]], Brian led the band in devising novel approaches to [[record producer|music production]], [[arranging]] his compositions for [[studio orchestra]]s, and experimenting with several [[musical genre|genres]] ranging from [[pop ballad]]s to [[psychedelic rock|psychedelic]] and [[baroque pop|baroque]] styles.

The group began as a [[garage band]] managed by the Wilsons' father [[Murry Wilson|Murry]], with [[Musicianship of Brian Wilson|Brian's creative ambitions and sophisticated songwriting abilities]] dominating the group's musical direction. After 1964, their albums took a different stylistic path that featured more personal lyrics, multi-layered sounds, and recording experiments. In 1966, the ''[[Pet Sounds]]'' album and "[[Good Vibrations]]" single vaulted the group to the top level of rock innovators and established the band as symbols of the [[counterculture of the 1960s|nascent counterculture era]]. Following ''[[Smile (The Beach Boys album)|Smile]]''{{'}}s [[Collapse of Smile|dissolution]], Brian gradually ceded production and songwriting duties to the rest of the band, reducing his input because of [[mental health]] and [[substance abuse]] issues. The group's public image subsequently faltered, and they struggled to reclaim their commercial momentum in America. The continued success of their [[greatest hits album]]s during the mid 1970s precipitated the band's transition into an [[oldies]] act, a move that was [[Cultural impact of the Beach Boys#Critical review|denigrated by critics and many fans]]. Since the 1980s, much-publicized legal wrangling over royalties, [[Love v. Wilson|songwriting credits]] and use of the band's name transpired.

Dennis drowned in 1983 and Carl died of lung cancer in 1998. After Carl's death, many live configurations of the band fronted by Mike Love and [[Bruce Johnston]] continued to tour into the 2000s while other members pursued solo projects. For the band's 50th anniversary, all the current surviving members briefly reunited for a [[That's Why God Made the Radio|new studio album]] and [[The Beach Boys 50th Anniversary Reunion Tour|world tour]]. Even though Wilson and Jardine do not perform with Love and Johnston's band, they remain a part of the Beach Boys' corporation, [[Brother Records|Brother Records Inc]].

The Beach Boys are [[cultural impact of the Beach Boys|regarded as the most iconic American band]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Jon|title=It's a Beach Boys Summer|url=http://www.newsmax.com/JonFriedman/Beach-Boys-Summer-Wilson/2012/06/18/id/442618/|work=[[Newsmax]]|date=June 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Garasa|first1=Cesareo|title=The fair: Beach Boys' return 'like a homecoming'|url=http://www.bakersfield.com/entertainment/2015/09/16/to-bakersfield-with-love-beach-boys-return-like-a-homecoming.html|work=[[The Bakersfield Californian]]|date=September 16, 2015}}</ref> and one of the most critically acclaimed, commercially successful, and widely influential bands of all time,<ref name="Vogue2015">{{cite magazine|last1=Seymour|first1=Corey|title=Love & Mercy Does Justice to the Brilliance of Brian Wilson|magazine=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|date=June 5, 2015|url=http://www.vogue.com/13266664/love-and-mercy-brian-wilson/}}</ref> while [[AllMusic]] stated that their "unerring ability... made them America's first, best rock band."<ref name="allmusic">[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p3640|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic "The Beach Boys – Overview"]. John Bush. [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved July 12, 2008.</ref> The group had over eighty songs chart worldwide, thirty-six of them US [[Top 40]] hits (the most by an American rock band), four reaching number-one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart.<ref name="allmusic"/> The Beach Boys have sold in excess of 100 million records worldwide, making them one of the [[List of best-selling music artists|world's best-selling bands of all time]] and are listed at number 12 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's 2004 list of the "100 Greatest Artists of All Time".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20130510/NEWS/130509772?p=2&tc=pg|title=The Beach Boys to play Tuscaloosa Amphitheater on Oct. 17|first=Cobb|last=Mark Hughes|publisher=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=May 10, 2013 |accessdate=May 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/9600643/Brian-Wilson-blindsided-by-Beach-Boys-sacking.html|title= Brian Wilson 'blindsided' by Beach Boys 'sacking' |date=October 11, 2012|first=Hannah|last=Furness|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=April 13, 2013|location=London}}<br />{{cite web| title = The Immortals: The First Fifty| work = Rolling Stone Issue 946| publisher = Rolling Stone| url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-artists-of-all-time-19691231 |accessdate=December 16, 2010}}</ref> They received their first and only [[Grammy Award]] for ''[[The Smile Sessions]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://au.eonline.com/news/386489/2013-grammy-awards-winners-the-complete-list|title=2013 Grammy Awards Winners: The Complete List|date=February 10, 2013|accessdate=April 12, 2013|author=Alyssa Toomey and Rosemary Brennan|work=[[E!]]}}</ref> The core quintet of the three Wilsons, Love and Jardine were inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in 1988.<ref name=RockHallofFame>{{cite web|title=The Beach Boys Biography|url=http://rockhall.com/inductees/the-beach-boys/bio/|publisher=Rock & Roll Hall of Fame|accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref>
{{toclimit|3}}

== 1958–66: Brian Wilson era ==

=== Formation ===
{{BLP sources section|date=June 2013}}

[[File:Beach Boys Landmark - Plano general I.jpg|thumb|right|[[Beach Boys Historic Landmark|The historical landmark in Hawthorne, California]] marking where the Wilson family home once stood]]

At the time of his sixteenth birthday on June 20, 1958, Brian Wilson shared a bedroom with his brothers, [[Dennis Wilson|Dennis]] and [[Carl Wilson|Carl]] – aged thirteen and eleven, respectively – in their family home in [[Hawthorne, California|Hawthorne]]. He had watched his father, [[Murry Wilson]], play piano, and had listened intently to the harmonies of vocal groups such as [[the Four Freshmen]].{{sfn|Lambert|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=7XsZAQAAIAAJ |page= 3}} 3]}} After dissecting songs such as "[[Ivory Tower (1956 song)|Ivory Tower]]" and "[[Good News (musical)|Good News]]", Brian would teach family members how to sing the background harmonies.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 12}} 12]}} For his birthday that year, Brian received a [[Reel-to-reel audio tape recording|reel-to-reel tape recorder]]. He learned how to [[overdub]], using his vocals and those of Carl and their mother.{{sfn|Lambert|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=7XsZAQAAIAAJ |page= 3}} 3]}} Brian played piano with Carl and [[David Marks]], an eleven-year-old longtime neighbor, playing guitars they had each received as Christmas presents.{{sfn|Stebbins|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=bnQIAQAAMAAJ|page= 18}} 18]}}

Soon Brian and Carl were avidly listening to [[Johnny Otis]]' [[KFOX (AM)|KFOX radio]] show.{{sfn|Lambert|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=7XsZAQAAIAAJ |page= 3}} 3]}} Inspired by the simple structure and vocals of the [[rhythm and blues]] songs he heard, Brian changed his piano-playing style and started writing songs.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} His enthusiasm interfered with his music studies at school. Family gatherings brought the Wilsons in contact with cousin [[Mike Love]]. Brian taught Love's sister Maureen and a friend harmonies.{{sfn|Lambert|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=7XsZAQAAIAAJ |page= 3}} 3]}} Later, Brian, Mike Love and two friends performed at [[Hawthorne High School (Hawthorne, California)|Hawthorne High School]].{{sfn|Lambert|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=7XsZAQAAIAAJ |page= 5}} 5]}} Brian also knew [[Al Jardine]], a high school classmate who had already played guitar in a folk group called the Islanders.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} Brian suggested to Jardine that they team up with his cousin and brother Carl. Love gave the fledgling band its name: "The Pendletones",{{sfn|Lambert|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=7XsZAQAAIAAJ |page= 21}} 21]}} a portmanteau of "[[Pendleton Woolen Mills|Pendleton]]", a style of woolen shirt popular at the time and "[[Musical tone|tone]]", the musical term. Though [[surfing]] motifs were prominent in their early songs, Dennis was the only avid surfer in the group.<ref name=pc20/> He suggested that the group compose songs that celebrated the sport and the lifestyle that it had inspired in [[Southern California]].<ref name=RockHallofFame/>{{sfn|Warner|1992|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=mTM_9JTeoMIC|page= 328}} 328]}}{{refn|group=nb|[[Nick Venet]] has said that none of the members, including Dennis, surfed until after the fact.{{sfn|Hoskyns|2009|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=w7oB2UKVxgQC|page= 60}} 60]}} }}

Jardine and a singer friend, Gary Winfrey, went to Brian to see if he could help out with a version of a folk song they wanted to record—"[[Sloop John B]]".{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} In Brian's absence, the two spoke with their father, a music industry veteran of modest success. Murry arranged for the Pendletones to meet his publisher, Hite Morgan.<ref name=RockHallofFame /> The group performed a slower ballad, "[[Their Hearts Were Full of Spring]]", but failed to impress Morgan. After an awkward pause, Dennis mentioned they had an original song, "[[Surfin' (song)|Surfin']]".{{citation needed|date=December 2014}} Brian finished the song, and together with Mike Love, wrote "[[Surfin' Safari (song)|Surfin' Safari]]".{{sfn|Warner|1992|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=mTM_9JTeoMIC|page= 328}} 328]}} The group rented guitars, drums, amplifiers and microphones, and practiced for three days while the Wilsons' parents were on a short vacation.

In October 1961, the Pendletones recorded the two surfing song demos in twelve takes at Keen Recording Studio.{{sfn|Warner|1992|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=mTM_9JTeoMIC|page= 328}} 328]}}{{failed verification|date=December 2014}}{{refn|group=nb|David Marks was not present at the session as he was in school that day.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/exclusive-q-a-original-beach-boy-david-marks-on-the-bands-anniversary-tour-20120316 |title=Exclusive QA: Original Beach Boy David Marks on the Band's Anniversary Tour &#124; Music News |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=March 16, 2012 |accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>}} Murry brought the demos to Herb Newman, owner of [[Candix Records]] and [[Era Records]], and he signed the group on December 8, 1961.{{sfn|Warner|1992|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=mTM_9JTeoMIC|page= 328}} 328]}} When the boys eagerly unpacked the first box of singles – released both under the Candix label, and also as a promo issue under X Records (Morgan's label) – they were shocked to see their band had been renamed as the Beach Boys.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}} Murry Wilson called Morgan{{citation needed|date=December 2014}} and learned that Candix wanted to name the group the Surfers to directly associate them with the increasingly popular teen sport. But [[Russ Regan]], a young promoter with Era Records – who later became president of [[20th Century Fox Records]] – noted that there already existed a group by that name, and he suggested calling them the Beach Boys.{{sfn|Warner|1992|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=mTM_9JTeoMIC|page= 328}} 328]}}

=== Beach-themed period ===
{{Main|Surfin' Safari|Surfin' U.S.A.|Surfer Girl|Little Deuce Coupe|Shut Down Volume 2|All Summer Long (album)}}

{{listen|filename= The Beach Boys - I Get Around.ogg|title= "I Get Around" (1964)|description=An excerpt from Brian Wilson and Mike Love's "I Get Around" that demonstrates Love's iconic nasal delivery and a surf-rock-styled guitar solo played by Carl Wilson. "I Get Around" became the band's first US number one charting song.<ref>{{cite web|last=Guarisco |first=Donald A. |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/i-get-around-mt0034419959 |title=I Get Around – The Beach Boys : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>}}

[[File:Beach Boys 1963.jpg|thumb|left|In [[Pendleton Woolen Mills|Pendleton]] outfits, performing at a local high school in late 1962]]

Released in December 1961, "[[Surfin']]" soon aired on [[KFWB]] and [[KRLA]], two of Los Angeles' most influential teen radio stations.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} It was a hit on the West Coast, going to number three in Southern California, and peaked at number 75 on the national pop charts. By the final weeks of 1961 "Surfin'" had sold more than 40,000 copies.<ref name="photobucket13">[http://i351.photobucket.com/albums/q476/marcus1970/hit%20parader%201966/HitParaderp6October1966.jpg "The Beach Boy Empire" Taylor, Derek. October 5, 1966. Hit Parader, p13]</ref> By this time the [[de facto]] manager of the Beach Boys, Murry Wilson landed the group's first paying gig (for which they earned $300) on New Year's Eve, 1961, at the [[Ritchie Valens]] Memorial Dance in [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]],{{sfn|Warner|1992|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=mTM_9JTeoMIC|page= 328}} 328]}} headlined by [[Ike & Tina Turner]].{{citation needed|date=December 2014}} In their earliest public appearances, the band wore heavy wool jacket-like shirts that local surfers favored {{sfn|Sanchez|2014|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=FC0_AwAAQBAJ|page= 19}} 19]}} before switching to their trademark striped shirts and white pants.{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=sLEMdjRhDgQC|page= 187}} 187]}}{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=106}} 106]}} Murry effectively seized managerial control of the band, and Brian acknowledged that he "deserves credit for getting us off the ground&nbsp;... he hounded us mercilessly&nbsp;... [but] also worked hard himself."{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

In the first half of February 1962, Jardine left the band and was replaced by Marks. The band recorded two more originals on April 19 at Western Studios, Los Angeles: "Lonely Sea" and "[[409 (song)|409]]". They also re-recorded "[[Surfin' Safari (song)|Surfin' Safari]]".{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} {{anchor|Kenny & the Cadets}} During early 1962, Morgan requested that some of the members add vocals to a couple of instrumental tracks that he had recorded with other musicians. This led to the creation of the short-lived group Kenny & the Cadets, which Brian led under the pseudonym "Kenny". The other members were Carl, Jardine, and the Wilsons' mother Audree.{{refn|group=nb|The only songs the group recorded were two Morgan compositions, "Barbie" and "What Is a Young Girl Made Of?"<ref>{{cite web|authorlink=Richie Unterberger|last=Unterberger|first=Richie|title=Kenny & the Cadets|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/kenny-the-cadets-mn0000070397|website=[[Allmusic]]}}</ref>}}

On June 4, the Beach Boys released their second single "Surfin' Safari" backed with "409". The release prompted national coverage in the June 9 issue of ''[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]''. The magazine praised Love's lead vocal and said the song had strong hit potential.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=June 9, 1962 |title=Reviews of New Singles |magazine=Billboard Magazine |volume= 74 |issue= 23 |page=40 |publisher= Nielsen Business Media, Inc. |doi= |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=sSkEAAAAMBAJ|page=4}} |accessdate=April 27, 2013}}</ref> On July 16, 1962—after being turned down by [[Dot Records|Dot]] and [[Liberty Records|Liberty]]—the Beach Boys signed a seven-year contract with [[Capitol Records]], based on the strength of the June demo session.<ref name="photobucket13"/> This was at the urging of Capitol exec [[Nick Venet]] who signed the group, seeing them as the "teenage gold" he had been scouting for.{{sfn|Hoskyns|2009|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=w7oB2UKVxgQC|page= 62}} 62]}} By November, their first album was ready—''Surfin' Safari'', which reached 32 on the US Billboard charts. Their song output continued along the same commercial line, focusing on California youth lifestyle.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 71}} 71]}}<ref name=pc20>{{Gilliland |url=http://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19770/m1/ |title=Show 20 – Forty Miles of Bad Road: Some of the best from rock 'n' roll's dark ages. [Part 1&#93; : UNT Digital Library |accessdate=November 5, 2011}}</ref>

In January 1963, three months after the release of their debut album, the band began recording their sophomore effort, ''Surfin' U.S.A.'', a breakthrough for Brian, who began asserting himself as songwriter and arranger.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 71}} 71]}} The LP was the start of Brian's penchant for [[doubletracking]] vocals,{{sfn|Trynka|Bacon|1996|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=HDrIjd5FQ8QC|page= 126}} 126]}} a pioneering innovation.{{sfn|Howard|2004|p=56}} Released on March 25, 1963, ''Surfin' U.S.A.'', met a more enthusiastic reception, reaching number two on the Billboard charts.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}} This propelled the band into a nationwide spotlight, and was vital to launching surf music as a national craze.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 71}} 71]}} Five days prior to the release of ''Surfin' U.S.A.'', Brian produced "[[Surf City (song)|Surf City]]", a song he had written for [[Jan and Dean]]. "Surf City" hit number one on the ''Billboard'' charts in July 1963, a development that pleased Brian but angered Murry, who felt his son had "given away" what should have been the Beach Boys' first chart-topper.{{sfn|Gaines|1986|pp=103–104}}

At the beginning of a tour of the Mid-West in April 1963, Jardine rejoined the Beach Boys at Brian's request.<ref name="The Beach Boys">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebeachboys.com/home.aspx |title=The Beach Boys |publisher=The Beach Boys |accessdate=November 23, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327211659/http://thebeachboys.com/home.aspx |archivedate=March 27, 2010 }}</ref> As he began playing live gigs again, Brian left the road to focus on writing and recording. The result of this arrangement produced the albums ''Surfer Girl'', released on September 16, 1963 and ''Little Deuce Coupe'', released less than a month later on October 7, 1963. This sextet incarnation of the Beach Boys did not extend beyond these two albums, as Marks officially left the band in early October because of conflict with manager Murry, pulling Brian back into touring.<ref>{{cite web |title=GIGS63 |first=Andrew G. |last=Doe |authorlink= |year=2012 |accessdate=October 26, 2012 |url=http://www.esquarterly.com/bellagio/gigs63.html}}</ref>

{{Quote box
 |quote  = We all studied in conservatories; we were trained musicians. We thought it was a fluke at first, but then we realized Brian was writing these incredible songs. This was not just a young kid writing about high school and surfing.
 |source =—[[Hal Blaine]], session drummer{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=46}}
 |width  = 25%
 |align  = right}}

Around this time, Brian began using members of [[The Wrecking Crew (music)|the Wrecking Crew]] to augment his increasingly demanding studio arrangements.{{sfn|Trynka|Bacon|1996|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=HDrIjd5FQ8QC|page= 127}} 127]}} Session musicians that participated on Wilson's productions were said to have been awestruck by his musical abilities.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=46}} For composer [[Frank Zappa]], the most exciting thing to him in "white-person-music" was when the Beach Boys used the progression V–II on "[[Little Deuce Coupe (song)|Little Deuce Coupe]]", calling it "an important step forward by going backward."{{sfn|Zappa|1989|p=187}} The band released a standalone Christmas-themed single, "[[Little Saint Nick]]", in December 1963, backed with an [[a cappella]] rendition of the [[Lord's Prayer|scriptural]] song "[[The Lord's Prayer (1935 song)|The Lord's Prayer]]". The A-side peaked at number 3 on the US ''Billboard'' Christmas chart.{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=45}}

[[File:The Beach Boys (1965).png|thumb|left|The group pictured in 1964]]

Following a successful Australasian tour in January and February 1964, the band returned home to face the [[British Invasion]] through the Beatles appearances on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]''. Also representing the Beatles, Capitol support for the Beach Boys immediately began waning. This caused Murry to fight for the band at the label more than before, often visiting their offices without warning to "twist executive arms."{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 50}} 50]}} Brian reacted to the Beatles bemusedly: "I was flipping out. I couldn't understand how a group could be just yelled and screamed at. The music they made, '[[I Want to Hold Your Hand]]' for example, wasn't even that great a record, but they just screamed at it. ... It got us off our asses in the studio. We started cutting – we said 'look, don't worry about the Beatles, we'll cut our own stuff."<ref>{{cite AV media|people=[[David Espar|Espar, David]], [[Robert Levi|Levi, Robert]] (Directors)|year=1995|title=Rock & Roll|medium=[[Miniseries]]|url=|ref=harv}}</ref> Reportedly,{{by whom|date=December 2014}} Brian wanted more time to complete their next album, yet Capitol insisted they finish recording swiftly to avoid being forgotten in the throes of the impending invasion.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} Satisfying these demands, the band hastily finished the sessions on February 20, 1964 and titled the album ''Shut Down Volume 2''. "[[Fun, Fun, Fun]]" was released as a single from the album (backed with "[[Why Do Fools Fall in Love (song)|Why Do Fools Fall in Love]]") and was a major hit. The LP, while containing several [[filler (media)|filler tracks]], was propelled by other songs such as the melancholic "[[The Warmth of the Sun]]" and the advanced production style of "[[Don't Worry Baby]]".{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|pp=71}}

[[File:Sullivan Beach Boys.jpg|thumb|right|Performing "I Get Around" on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' in September 1964 ]]

Brian soon wrote his last surf song in April 1964.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 51}} 51]}} That month, during recording of the single "[[I Get Around]]", Murry was relieved of his duties as manager. Brian reflected, "We love the family thing – y'know: three brothers, a cousin and a friend is a really beautiful way to have a group – but the extra generation can become a hang-up."<ref name="photobucket13"/> When the single was released in May of that year, it would climb to number one, their first single to do so, proving that the Beach Boys could compete with contemporaneous British pop groups.{{sfn|Moskowitz|2015|p=42}} Two months later, the album that the song appeared on, ''All Summer Long'', reached number four on the Billboard 200 charts. ''All Summer Long'' introduced exotic textures to the Beach Boys' sound exemplified by the [[piccolo]]s and [[xylophone]]s of [[All Summer Long (The Beach Boys song)|its title track]].{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=110}} 110]}} The album was a swan-song to the surf and car music the Beach Boys built their commercial standing upon. Later albums took a different stylistic and lyrical path.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|pp=72–73}} Before this, a live album, ''[[Beach Boys Concert]]'', was released in October to a four-week chart stay at number one, containing a setlist of previously recorded hits and [[cover version|covers]] that they had not yet recorded.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 72}} 72]}} It was the first live album that ever topped pop music record charts.{{sfn|Moskowitz|2015|p=42}}

=== ''Today!'' and ''Summer Days'' ===
{{Main|The Beach Boys' Christmas Album|The Beach Boys Today!|Summer Days (And Summer Nights!!)|Beach Boys' Party!}}

{{Quote box
 |quote  = We needed to grow. Up to this point we had milked every idea dry. We milked it fucking dry. We had done every possible angle about surfing and then we did the car routine. But we needed to grow
artistically.
 |source =—Brian Wilson quoted in ''[[Teen Beat]]''{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=54}}<ref name=HimesSurf />
 |width  = 25%
 |align  = right}}

In June 1964, Brian began recording the bulk of ''The Beach Boys' Christmas Album'' with a forty-one-piece studio orchestra in collaboration with [[The Four Freshmen|Four Freshmen]] arranger [[Dick Reynolds (musician)|Dick Reynolds]]. Released in December, it was divided between five new, original Christmas-themed songs, and seven reinterpretations of traditional Christmas songs.{{sfn|Sanchez|2014|pp=59–60}} It would be regarded as one of the finest [[holiday album]]s of the rock era.{{sfn|Moskowitz|2015|p=42}} One single from the album, "[[The Man with All the Toys]]", was released, peaking at number 6 on the US ''Billboard'' Christmas chart.{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=75}} On October 29, the Beach Boys performed for ''[[The T.A.M.I. Show]]'', a concert film intended to bring together a wide range of hit-making musicians for a one-off performance. The result was released to movie theaters one month later.{{sfn|Sanchez|2014|pp=30–31}}

[[File:The Beach Boys (8794913159).jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|During a 1964 photoshoot]]

By the end of the year, the stress of road travel, composing, producing and maintaining a high level of creativity became too much for Brian. On December 23, while on a flight from Los Angeles to Houston, he suffered a [[panic attack]] only hours after performing with the Beach Boys on the [[variety show|musical variety series]] ''[[Shindig!]]''.{{sfn|Sanchez|2014|pp=63–64}} In January 1965, he announced his withdrawal from touring to concentrate entirely on songwriting and record production. For the rest of 1964 and into 1965, [[Glen Campbell]] served as Wilson's temporary replacement in concert, until his own career success pulled him from the group in April 1965.<ref>{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p1543|label=Glen Campbell|accessdate=April 23, 2011}}</ref> Bruce Johnston was asked to locate a replacement for Campbell; having failed to find one, Johnston himself became a full-time member of the band on May 19, 1965, first replacing Brian on the road and later contributing in the studio, beginning with the vocal sessions for "[[California Girls]]" on June 4, 1965.<ref>{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p18553|label=Bruce Johnston|accessdate=April 23, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquarterly.com/bellagio/gigs65.html |title=GIGS65 |publisher=Esquarterly.com |accessdate=May 22, 2013}}</ref>

After Brian stopped touring in 1965, he became a full-time studio artist, showcasing a great leap forward with ''The Beach Boys Today!'', an album containing a suite-like structure divided by songs and [[ballad]]s, and portended the [[Album Era]] with its cohesive artistic statement.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=111}} 111]}} During the recording sessions for ''Today!'', Love told [[Melody Maker]] that he and the band wanted to look beyond [[surf rock]] and to avoid living in the past or resting on their laurels.<ref name=Welch1964>{{cite magazine|last1=Welch|first1=C|title=Beach Boys Brought their own vegetables – so audiences beware!|magazine=Melody Maker|date=November 14, 1964|page=18}}</ref> The resulting LP had largely guitar-oriented pop songs such as "[[Dance, Dance, Dance (song)|Dance, Dance, Dance]]" and "[[Good to My Baby]]" on side A with B-side ballads such as "[[Please Let Me Wonder]]" and "[[She Knows Me Too Well]]".{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 72}} 72]}}<ref>{{cite web |url =http://www.allmusic.com/song/dance-dance-dance-t14595755| title =Dance, Dance, Dance| publisher = Allmusic}}</ref>

{{listen|filename=Let_Him_Run_Wild.ogg|title = "Let Him Run Wild" from ''Summer Days (And Summer Nights!!)'' (1965)|description= "[[Let Him Run Wild]]" belongs to a group of many Wilson-Love songs from 1965 that incorporate higher production values, denser arrangements, and more personal lyrics.<ref>{{cite web|last=Greenwald |first=Matthew |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/let-him-run-wild-mt0032095649 |title=Let Him Run Wild – The Beach Boys : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>}}

''Today!'' established the Beach Boys as album artists{{sfn|Moskowitz|2015|p=43}} and marked a maturation in their lyric content by abandoning themes related to surfing, cars, or teenage love. Some love songs remained, but with a marked increase in depth, along with introspective tracks accompanied by adventurous and distinct arrangements.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=111}} 111]}}{{sfn|Howard|2004|p=58}} While the band's contemporaries grew more intellectually aware, Capitol continued to bill them as "America’s Top Surfin' Group!" expecting Brian to write more surfing material for the yearly summer markets despite his disinterest.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 62}} 62]}}

In June 1965, the band released ''Summer Days (And Summer Nights!!)''. The album included a reworked arrangement of "[[Help Me, Rhonda]]" which became the band's second number one single in the spring of 1965, displacing the Beatles' "[[Ticket to Ride]]". "[[Let Him Run Wild]]" tapped into the youthful angst that later pervaded their music.{{according to|date=August 2014}} In November 1965, the group followed their US number-three-charting "California Girls" from ''Summer Days (And Summer Nights!!)'' with another top-twenty single, "[[The Little Girl I Once Knew]]". It was considered the band's most experimental statement thus far,{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 72}} 72]}} using silence as a pre-chorus, clashing keyboards, moody brass and vocal tics.{{according to|date=August 2014}} The single continued Brian's ambitions for daring arrangements, featuring unexpected tempo changes and numerous false endings.{{sfn|Howard|2004|p=59}} Perhaps too extreme an arrangement{{according to|date=August 2014}}  to go much higher than its number 20 peak, it was the band's second single not to reach the top ten since their 1962 breakthrough.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}

Capitol demanded a Beach Boys LP for the 1965 Christmas season, and to appease them, Brian conceived ''Beach Boys' Party!'', a live-in-the-studio album consisting mostly of acoustic covers of 1950s rock and R&B songs, in addition to covers of three Beatles songs, [[Bob Dylan]]'s "[[The Times They Are a-Changin' (song)|The Times They Are a-Changin']]", and idiosyncratic rerecordings of the group's earlier hits.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 71}} 71]}} In December they scored an unexpected number two hit (number three in the UK) with "[[Barbara Ann]]", which Capitol released as a single with no band input. Originally by [[the Regents]], it became one of the Beach Boys' most recognized hits.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}

=== ''Pet Sounds'' ===
{{Main|Pet Sounds}}

{{Listen
|pos=right
|filename= The Beach Boys - God only knows.ogg
|title="God Only Knows" from ''Pet Sounds'' (1966)
|description="[[God Only Knows]]" was one of the first commercial pop songs to use the word "God" in its title.{{sfn|Kent|2009|p=17}}
}}

In 1966, the Beach Boys formally established their use of unconventional instruments and elaborate layers of vocal harmonies on their album ''Pet Sounds''.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 72}} 72]}}{{sfn|Tunbridge|2010|p=173}} It is considered Brian's most concise demonstration of his production and songwriting expertise.{{sfn|MacFarlane|2008|pp=37–38}}{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=113}} 113]}} With songs such as "[[Wouldn't It Be Nice]]" and "[[Sloop John B]]", the album's innovative [[soundscape]] incorporates elements of [[jazz music|jazz]], [[classical music|classical]], pop, [[exotica]], and the [[avant-garde music|avant-garde]].{{sfn|Stebbins|2011|p=151}} The instrumentation combines [[found sound]]s such as [[bicycle bell]]s and dog whistles with classically inspired orchestrations and the usual rock set-up of drums and guitars;{{sfn|Tunbridge|2010|p=173}}{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 72}} 72]}} among others, [[silver (household)|silverware]], [[accordion]]s, plucked piano strings, barking dogs, and plastic water jugs.<ref name="Davis1990"/> For the basic rhythmic feel for "[[God Only Knows]]", [[harpsichord]], piano with [[slapback echo]], [[sleigh bell]]s, and [[string section|strings]] [[spill (audio)|spilled]] into each other to create a rich blanket of sound.{{sfn|Zak|2001|p=88}}

Released in May, ''Pet Sounds'' eventually peaked at number eleven in the US and number two in the UK.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=85, 88}}{{verification needed|date=December 2014}} This helped the Beach Boys become the strongest selling album act in the UK for the final quarter of 1966, dethroning the three-year reign of native bands such as the Beatles.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Andrews |first1=Grame |date=March 4, 1967 |title=Americans Regain Rule in England |magazine=Billboard Magazine |volume= 79 |issue= 9 |pages=1, 10 |publisher= Nielsen Business Media, Inc. |doi= |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=CykEAAAAMBAJ|page=1}} |accessdate=April 27, 2013}}{{verification needed|date=October 2014}}</ref> Met with a lukewarm critical reception in the US,{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=85}} ''Pet Sounds'' was indifferently promoted by Capitol and failed to become the major hit Wilson had hoped it would be.<ref name=pc37>{{Gilliland|url=http://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19796/m1/ |title=Show 37 – The Rubberization of Soul: The great pop music renaissance. [Part 3&#93; : UNT Digital Library |accessdate=Novemver 11, 2011}}</ref> Its failure to gain a wider recognition in the US combined with Capitol's decision to issue ''[[Best of The Beach Boys]]'' in July dispirited Brian, who considered ''Pet Sounds'' an extremely personal work.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=85–86}} Some assumed that the label considered the album a risk, appealing more to an older demographic than the younger, female audience the Beach Boys built their commercial standing on.{{sfn|Jones|2008|p=47}} ''Pet Sounds'' sales numbered approximately 500,000 units, a significant drop-off from the chain of million-selling albums that immediately preceded it.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 85}} 85]}} ''Best of The Beach Boys'' was quickly certified Gold by the [[RIAA]].{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 86}} 86]}}

[[File:Brian Wilson I Just Wasn't Made For These Times.png|thumb|left|200px|Brian Wilson working at a ''[[Pet Sounds]]'' session in early 1966]]

''Pet Sounds'' is considered by some as a Brian Wilson solo album in all but name, as other members contributed relatively little to the compositions or recordings.{{sfn|Hoskyns|2009|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=w7oB2UKVxgQC|page= 106}} 106]}}{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 72}} 72]}}{{sfn|Jones|2008|p=41}} Influenced by [[psychedelic drug]]s, Brian turned inward and probed his deep-seated self-doubts and emotional longings; the piece did not address the problems in the world around them, unlike other [[psychedelic rock]] groups.{{sfn|DeRogatis|2003|pp=34–35}} As [[Jim Miller (musician)|Jim Miller]] wrote of the album's tone, "[It] vented Wilson's obsession with isolation cataloging a forlorn quest for security. The whole enterprise, which smacked of [[song cycle]] pretensions, was streaked with regret and romantic languor."{{sfn|Miller|1992|p=195}} According to Brian, the album was designed as a collection of art pieces that belong together yet could stand alone.{{sfn|Tunbridge|2010|p=174}}<ref name="PopGenius"/> In a 1972 retrospective review of the album, music journalist [[Stephen Davis (music journalist)|Stephen Davis]] wrote: "From first cut to last we were treated to an intense, linear personal vision of the vagaries of a love affair and the painful, introverted anxieties that are the wrenching precipitates of the unstable chemistry of any love relationship. This trenchant cycle of love songs has the emotional impact of a shatteringly evocative novel ... nobody was prepared for anything so soulful, so lovely, something one had to think about so much."<ref name="Davis1972">{{cite web|first=Stephen|last=Davis|authorlink=Stephen Davis (music journalist)|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/pet-sounds-19720622 |title=Pet Sounds |work=Rolling Stone |date=June 22, 1972 }}</ref>

''Pet Sounds'' was massively influential upon its release, vaunting the band to the top level of rock innovators.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 72}} 72]}} It is one of the earliest rock concept albums,{{sfn|Moorefield|2010|p=16}}<ref name="Davis1972"/> one of the earliest concept albums of the [[counterculture of the 1960s|counterculture era]],{{sfn|Perone|2004|p=161}} and an early album in the emerging psychedelic rock style,{{sfn|DeRogatis|2003}} signaling a turning point wherein rock, which previously had been considered dance music, became music that was made for listening to.{{sfn|Martin|1998|p=39}} In 2016, ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Barbara Ellen reflected that the album was "hailed as a revolution in harmonies and production techniques ... Wilson single-handedly reinvented the album as the in-depth illumination of an artist’s soul, kicking open a creative fire-door, liberating the album to exist as a self-contained art form on a par with literature, theatre, art, cinema, dance… anything the artist desired."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ellen|first1=Barbara|title=Was 1966 pop music’s greatest year?|url=http://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/31/three-albums-1966-beatles-revolver-bob-dylan-blonde-on-blonde-beach-boys-pet-sounds|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=January 31, 2016}}</ref> Reflecting on the album on its 50th anniversary, ''PopMatters''{{'}} Danilo Castro added:

{{quote|The resulting recordings were colossal achievements, as conventional instruments seamlessly meshed with glockenspiels, ukulele, [[Electro-Theremin]], bongos, and harpsichords. ... His insistence upon exact musical cues, unconventional structure, and experimental trickery made for a final product that radiates originality. ... Praised by every rocker from the Beatles to [[Bob Dylan]], the latter who said Wilson’s left ear should be donated to the Smithsonian, the Beach Boys were suddenly spearheading the pop revolution. ... Since that day in May ... ''Pet Sounds'' has become a pillar of pop excellence. ... it's restructured the landscape of modern music in its image.<ref name="Castro2016">{{cite web|last1=Castro|first1=Danilo|title=Why Does the Beach Boys' 'Pet Sounds' Still Have Its Hold on Us?|url=http://www.popmatters.com/feature/why-does-the-beach-boys-pet-sounds-still-have-its-hold-on-us/|website=''[[PopMatters]]''|date=May 16, 2016}}</ref>}}

[[File:God Only Knows - Rock and Roll Hall of Fame (2014-12-30 13.09.36 by Sam Howzit).jpg|thumb|right|An original "God Only Knows" lyric manuscript exhibited at the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in Cleveland, Ohio]]

In ''The Album: A Guide to Pop Music's Most Provocative, Influential, and Important Creations'', author James Perone championed the album for its complex orchestrations, sophisticated compositions, and varied [[tone color]]s, calling it a remove from "just about anything else that was going on in 1966 pop music."{{sfn|Perone|2012|pp=28–30}} In 1976, journalist [[Robin Denselow]] wrote: "With the 1966 ''Pet Sounds'' album ... Wilson had become America's equivalent of the Beatles with his ability to expand the limits of popular taste."<ref name="Riding a wave">{{cite news |first=Robin |last=Denselow |title=Feature: ''Riding a wave'' |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |issue=September 1, 1976 |page=8}}</ref> [[Paul McCartney]] named it one of his favorite albums of all time on multiple occasions, calling it the primary impetus for the Beatles' album ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' (1967).{{sfn|Jones|2008|p=57}} In 2003, ''Pet Sounds'' was ranked second in "[[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]" list selected by ''Rolling Stone'', behind only ''Sgt. Pepper''.{{sfn|Jones|2008|p=57}} In 2004, the album was acknowledged as an important historical and cultural work by the [[Library of Congress]].<ref name="PetSoundsCongress"/>

=== "Good Vibrations" and ''Smile'' ===
{{Main|Good Vibrations|Smile (The Beach Boys album)}}
{{Further|Collapse of Smile}}

{{Listen
|pos=right
|filename=Beach_Boys_-_Good_Vibrations.ogg
|title="Good Vibrations" (1966)
|description="[[Good Vibrations]]" was the Beach Boys' third single to top the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The song proliferated a wave of pop experimentation with its rush of riff changes, echo-chamber effects, and intricate harmonies.<ref>{{cite web|last1=John|first1=Bush|title=Review|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/good-vibrations-mt0028092523|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=November 16, 2014}}</ref>
}}

Seeking to expand on ''Pet Sounds''' advances, Wilson began an even more ambitious project: "[[Good Vibrations]]". Like ''Pet Sounds'', Brian opted for an eclectic array of instruments rarely heard in pop music.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=116}} 116]}} Described by Brian as a "[[pocket symphony]]",{{sfn|DeRogatis|2003|p=638}} it contains a mixture of classical, rock, and exotic instruments structured around a [[cut-up technique|cut-up mosaic]] of musical sections represented by several discordant key and modal shifts.{{sfn|Harrison|1997|pp=41–46}} It became the Beach Boys' biggest hit to date, and a US and UK number one single in 1966. Coming at a time when pop singles were usually made in under two hours, it was one of the most complex pop productions ever undertaken, and the most expensive single ever recorded to that point.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=116}} 116]}}{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 55}} 55]}}{{sfn|Harrison|1997|pp=41–46}} The production costs were estimated between $50,000 and $75,000  (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|50000|1966|r=-4}}}} and ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|75000|1966|r=-4}}}} today) with sessions for the song stretching over several months in at least four major studios.{{sfn|Harrison|1997|pp=41–46}} According to [[Domenic Priore]], the making of "Good Vibrations" was unlike anything previous in the realms of classical, jazz, international, soundtrack, or any other kind of recording.{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 55}} 55]}}

The single was an unequivocal milestone in studio productions,{{sfn|Perone|2004|p=16}}{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=116}} 116]}}{{sfn|Priore|2005|pp=55–56}}{{sfn|Howard|2004|p=66}} and continued in establishing Brian as an extender of popular tastes.<ref name="Riding a wave"/> To the counterculture of the 1960s, "Good Vibrations" served as an anthem.{{sfn|Guinn|2014|p=130}} Rock critic Gene Sculatti prophesied in 1968, "[It] may yet prove to be the most significantly revolutionary piece of the current rock renaissance."<ref name="Scalluti1968">{{cite magazine|last1=Sculatti|first1=Gene|url=http://www.teachrock.org/resources/article/villains-and-heroes-in-defense-of-the-beach-boys/|title=Villains and Heroes: In Defense of the Beach Boys|magazine=Jazz & Pop|date=September 1968|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> Its instrumentation included [[Paul Tanner]]'s [[Electro-Theremin]], a manually-operated oscillator with a sound similar to a [[theremin]], which helped the Beach Boys claim a new [[hippie]] audience.<ref>{{cite book|author=Heylin, C. Heylin|title=The Act You've Known For All These Years: the Life, and Afterlife, of Sgt. Pepper|location=London|publisher= Canongate Books|date= 2007|isbn=1-84195-955-3|page= 85}}</ref>{{sfn|Holmes|2012|p=415}}  Upon release, the single prompted an unexpected revival in theremins while increasing awareness of [[analog synthesizer]]s, leading [[Moog Music]] to produce their own brand of [[ribbon controller|ribbon-controlled]] instruments.{{sfn|Pinch|Trocco|2009|pp=102–3}} Reflecting on this period in 1971, ''[[New York (magazine)|Cue]]'' magazine wrote: "In the year and a half that followed ''Pet Sounds'', the Beach Boys were among the vanguard in practically every aspect of the counter culture – psychedelia, [[art rock]], a return to roots, ecology, organic food, the cooled-out sound – anticipating changes that rock didn't accomplish until 1969–1970."<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Pet Sounds|magazine=Cue|date=1971|volume=40|issue=27|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=EwgwAQAAIAAJ}}}}</ref>
The group established a short-lived film [[production company]], called Home Movies, during this time. It was supposed to have created live action film and television properties starring the Beach Boys. However, the company completed only one music video, for "Good Vibrations", though various other psychedelic sequences and segments exist.{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 116}} 116]}}

[[File:Van Dyke Parks 1967.png|thumb|right|[[Van Dyke Parks]], Brian's lyricist and collaborator for the unfinished album ''[[Smile (The Beach Boys album)|Smile]]'']]

Brian met lyricist and musician [[Van Dyke Parks]] while working on ''Pet Sounds''.{{sfn|Hoskyns|2009|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=w7oB2UKVxgQC|page= 129}} 129]}}{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=114}} A year later, while in the midst of recording "Good Vibrations", the duo began an intense collaboration that resulted in a suite of challenging new songs for the Beach Boys{{'}} forthcoming album ''Smile'', intended to surpass ''Pet Sounds''.{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=131}} Recording for the album spanned about a year, from 1966 to 1967.{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=390}} Wilson and Parks intended ''Smile'' to be a continuous suite of songs that were linked both thematically and musically, with the main songs being linked together by small vocal pieces and instrumental segments that elaborated upon the musical themes of the major songs.{{sfn|Williams|2010|pp=94–98}} Surviving recordings have shown that the music incorporated [[chanting]], [[cowboy song]]s, explorations in [[Native American music|Indian]] and [[Hawaiian music]], jazz, [[tone poem]]s with classical elements, [[cartoon]] sound effects, ''[[musique concrète]]'', and [[yodeling]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murphy|first1=Sean|title=The Once and Future King: 'SMiLE' and Brian Wilson’s Very American Dream|url=http://www.popmatters.com/feature/161935-the-once-and-future-king-smile-and-brian-wilsons-very-american-dream/|website=Popmatters|accessdate=July 17, 2014|date=August 28, 2012}}</ref>

{{Quote box| width=25%|align=left
| quote=I'm doing the spiritual sound, a white spiritual sound. [[Religious music]]...That's the whole movement...That's where I'm going and it's going to scare a lot of people when I get there.
| source=—[[Brian Wilson]] quoted in "[[Goodbye Surfing, Hello God!]]" (1967), by [[Jules Siegel]]<ref name="surfgod">{{cite book|author=Siegal, Jules Siegal|title=Goodbye Surfing, Hello God!|date=1967}}</ref>}}

In October 1966 interviews, Brian touted the album "a teenage symphony to God".{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=91}} His spiritual aims were made explicit in the album's musical contents and lyrics, which also included existential angst, the exploration of human innocence, and the philosophy of childlikeness.{{sfn|Sellars|2015|pp=8–9}} Parks has stated: he and Brian were conscious of the counterculture, and the two had felt estranged from it, but it was necessary to adhere to because of a willingness to "get out of the [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]] mindset."{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 39}} 39]}} Parks stresses, "At the same time, he didn't want to lose that kind of gauche sensibility that he had. He was doing stuff that nobody would dream of doing," citing an instance when Brian instructed a banjo player to play only one string, a "gauche" style of playing that "just wasn't done."{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 39}} 39]}}

''Smile'' would go on to become the most legendary unreleased album in the history of popular music.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 72}} 72]}}{{sfn|Jones|2008|p=63}} In the decades following its non-release, it became the subject of intense speculation and mystique.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=118}} 118]}}{{sfn|Harrison|1997|p=55}} Many believe that, had the album been released, it would have substantially altered the group's direction and established them at the vanguard of rock innovators.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=119}} 119]}} Writing about the album for the [[33⅓]] book series, Luis Sanchez stated: "If Brian Wilson and the Beach Boys were going to survive as the defining force of American pop music they were, ''Smile'' was a conscious attempt to rediscover the impulses and ideas that power American consciousness from the inside out. It was a collaboration that led to some incredible music, which, if it had been completed as an album and delivered to the public in 1966, might have had an incredible impact."{{sfn|Sanchez|2014|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=FC0_AwAAQBAJ|page= 112}} 112]}}

If released when intended, composer Frank Oteri believes the album would have been the first piece of [[album-oriented rock]]. Its cover artwork, now considered iconic, depicted an illustration of a store selling smiles, also would have been among the earliest covers by a popular music group to feature original, specifically commissioned artwork rather than a photograph of the performers.<ref name=Oteri2011>{{cite web|last1=Oteri|first1=Frank J.|title=SOUNDS HEARD: THE BEACH BOYS—THE SMILE SESSIONS|url=http://www.newmusicbox.org/articles/sounds-heard-the-beach-boys-the-smile-sessions/|website=New Music Box|accessdate=March 14, 2016|date=December 8, 2011}}</ref> Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, [[bootleg recording|bootlegs]] from its recording sessions leaked, inspiring many attempts to reassemble the album, and ultimately becoming a progenitor for [[indie rock]].<ref name=Oteri2011/>

Many factors [[Collapse of Smile|combined to put intense pressure on Brian Wilson]] as ''Smile'' neared completion: his mental instability, the pressure to create despite fierce internal opposition to his new music, the relatively unenthusiastic response to ''Pet Sounds'' in the United States, Carl Wilson's [[military draft|draft]] resistance, and a major dispute with [[Capitol Records]].{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} Furthermore, Wilson's reliance on both prescription drugs and [[amphetamine]]s exacerbated his underlying mental health problems. Comparable to [[Brian Jones]] and [[Syd Barrett]], Brian Wilson's use of psychedelic drugs—especially [[LSD]]—led to a nervous breakdown in the late-1960s.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} As his legend grew, the ''Smile'' period came to be seen as the pivotal episode in his decline, and he became tagged as a drug casualty.<ref name=Oteri2011/>

== 1967–77: fluctuating leadership ==

=== ''Smiley Smile'' and ''Wild Honey'' ===
{{Main|Smiley Smile|Wild Honey (album)}}
{{See also|Lei'd in Hawaii}}

{{Quote box
 |quote  = [By] 1967, the Beach Boys had become cultural dinosaurs. And it happened almost overnight....[[Monterey Pop Festival|Monterey]] was a gathering place for the "far out" sounds of the "new" rock, and the Beach Boys in concert really had no exotic sounds to display. The net result of all [their] internal and external turmoil was that the Beach Boys didn't go...and it is thought that this non-appearance was what really turned the "underground" tide against them.
 |source =—[[David Leaf]]<ref>{{cite AV media notes| title = Smiley Smile/Wild Honey | others= The Beach Boys| year = 1990| first = David| last = Leaf|authorlink=David Leaf|publisher=[[Capitol Records]]|type=CD Liner|url=http://www.albumlinernotes.com/Smiley_Smile_Wild_Honey.html}}</ref>
 |width  = 25%
 |align  = right
}}

Some ''Smile'' tracks were salvaged and re-recorded in scaled-down versions at [[Brian Wilson's home studio|Brian's new home studio]]. Along with the single version of "Good Vibrations", these tracks were released on the September 1967 album ''Smiley Smile'', which elicited positive critical and commercial response abroad, but was the first real commercial failure for the group in the United States.{{sfn|DeRogatis|1996|p=18}}  Compounding the group's recent setbacks, their public image took a cataclysmic hit following their withdrawal from the 1967 [[Monterey Pop Festival]]{{sfn|Guinn|2014|p=130}} for the reason that they had no new material to play while their forthcoming single and album lay in limbo.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 122}} 122]}} Their cancellation was seen as "...a damning admission that they were washed up [and] unable to compete with the new music."{{sfn|Gaines|1986|p=179}} This notion was exacerbated by ''Rolling Stone'' writer [[Jann Wenner]], who in contemporary publications criticized Brian Wilson for his oft-repeated "genius" label, which he called a "promotional shuck" and an attempt to compare him with the Beatles.{{sfn|Gaines|1986|p=179}}

While being interviewed in August 1967 for the aborted live album ''[[Lei'd in Hawaii]]'', Brian stated: "I think rock n' roll–the pop scene–is happening. It’s great. But I think basically, the Beach Boys are squares. We’re not happening."{{sfn|Stebbins|Rusten|2013}}{{page needed|date=April 2015}} Former band publicist [[Derek Taylor]] later recalled a conversation with Brian and Dennis where they denied that the group had ever written surf music or songs about cars, and that the Beach Boys had never been involved with the surf and hot rod fads, as Taylor claimed, "...they would not concede."{{sfn|Kent|2009|p=31}} As a result of their initial target demographic and subsequent failures to blend with the hippie movement, the group was viewed as unhip relics,{{sfn|Gaines|1986|p=154}} even though they had once been, as biographer [[Peter Ames Carlin]] wrote, "the absolute center of the American rock ’n’ roll scene,"{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 138}} 138]}} a time when they had ushered the psychedelic era.{{sfn|DeRogatis|2003|p=32}}{{sfn|McCleary|2004|p=42}} In early 1969, Brian proposed that the group change their name from "the Beach Boys" to "the Beach", reasoning that the band members were now grown men. Going to the effort of acquiring a contract that would declare a five-way agreement to officially rename the group, [[Stephen Desper]] reported, "They all just kind of shrugged and said, 'Aw, come on, Brian, we don't wanna do that. That's how the public knows us, man. And that was it. He put the paper on the piano and it stayed there until I picked it up and took it away."{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 147}} 147]}}

In 1966, the group had filed a lawsuit in the Los Angeles Superior Court against Capitol Records for over two million dollars, which briefly severed their relationship with the label. At this time the Beach Boys' management (Nick Grillo and [[David Anderle]]) created the band's own record label, [[Brother Records|Brother]]. One of the first labels owned by a rock group<ref name="books.google.co.uk">{{cite book|author=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|title=Billboard|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=ySgEAAAAMBAJ|page=3}}|date=April 12, 1969|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|pages=3–|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> Brother Records was intended for releases of Beach Boys side projects, and as an invitation to new talent.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} The initial output of the label, however, was limited to ''Smiley Smile'' and two resulting singles from the album. The failure of "[[Gettin' Hungry]]" caused the band to shelve Brother until 1970.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

{{Quote box
 |quote  = When we did ''Wild Honey'', Brian asked me to get more involved in the recording end. He wanted a break. he was tired. He had been doing it all too long.
 |source =—[[Carl Wilson]]<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Beach Boys|magazine=Music Favorites|volume=1|issue=2|date=1976}}</ref>
 |width  = 25%
 |align  = left
}}

After the cancellation of ''Smile'', some of its tracks continued to trickle out in later albums often as [[filler (media)|filler songs]] to offset Brian's unwillingness to contribute.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 148}} 148]}}{{refn|group=nb|The band was still expecting to complete and release ''Smile'' as late as 1973 before it became clear that only Brian could comprehend the endless fragments that had been recorded.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 179}} 179]}}}} ''Smiley Smile'' was followed up three months later with ''[[Wild Honey (album)|Wild Honey]]'', featuring mostly new songs written by Wilson and Love, including the number 19 single "[[Darlin' (The Beach Boys song)|Darlin']]". The album fared better than its predecessor, reaching number 24 in the US.{{failed verification|date=May 2016}} Wenner responded to the new album with more optimism, remarking two months later that "[in] any case it's good to see that the Beach Boys are getting their heads straight once again".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/wild-honey-19680224|accessdate=June 22, 2013|title=Wild Honey|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York|date=February 24, 1968}}</ref>

=== ''Friends'' and ''20/20'' ===
{{Main|Friends (The Beach Boys album)|20/20 (The Beach Boys album)}}

[[File:MahareshiYogi2.jpg|right|130px|thumb|alt=Closeup portrait of an Indian man with long black hair and mustache, and white beard|Maharishi Mahesh Yogi|[[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]] in 1973]]

After meeting [[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]] at a [[UNICEF]] Variety Gala in Paris, France on December 15, 1967, Love, along with other high-profile celebrities such as [[Donovan]] and [[the Beatles]] traveled to [[Rishikesh]] in India during February and March 1968.<ref>{{cite web |title=GIGS67 |first=Andrew G. |last=Doe |authorlink= |year=2012 |accessdate=October 26, 2012 |url=http://www.esquarterly.com/bellagio/gigs67.html}}</ref><ref name="Doe 2012">{{cite web |title=GIGS68 |first=Andrew G. |last=Doe |authorlink= |year=2012 |accessdate=October 26, 2012 |url=http://www.esquarterly.com/bellagio/gigs68.html}}</ref> The following Beach Boys album ''Friends'' (1968) had songs influenced by the [[Transcendental Meditation]] taught by the Maharishi. The album reached number 13 in the UK and 126 in the US, [[Friends (The Beach Boys song)|the title track]] placing at number 25 in the UK and number 47 in the US, the band's lowest singles peak since 1962. In support of the ''Friends'' album, Love had arranged for the Beach Boys to tour with the Maharishi in the US, which has been called "one of the more bizarre entertainments of the era."{{sfn|Frontani|2009|p=198}} Starting on May 3, 1968, the tour lasted five shows and was cancelled when the Maharishi had to withdraw to fulfill film contracts. Because of disappointing audience numbers and the Maharishi's withdrawal, twenty-four tour dates were subsequently cancelled at a cost estimated at US$250,000 (approximately US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|250000|1969|r=-4}}}} today) for the band.<ref name="Doe 2012"/>{{sfn|Gaines|1986|p=196}} This tour was followed by the release of "[[Do It Again (The Beach Boys song)|Do It Again]]", a single that critics described as an update of the Beach Boys' surf rock past in a late 1960s style.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.allmusic.com/song/do-it-again-t995511|title =Do It Again | publisher=Allmusic| accessdate=July 12, 2011}}</ref> The single went to the top of the Australian and UK single charts in 1968 and was moderately successful in the US, peaking at number 20.{{sfn|Warner|1992|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=mTM_9JTeoMIC|page= 330}} 330]}}

For a short time in mid-1968, Brian Wilson sought psychological treatment in hospital.{{sfn|Carlin|2006}} During his absence, other members began writing and producing material themselves. To complete their contract with Capitol, they produced one more album. ''20/20'' (1969) was one of the group's most stylistically diverse albums, including [[hard rock]] songs such as "[[All I Want to Do (The Beach Boys song)|All I Want to Do]]", the [[waltz]]-based "[[Time to Get Alone]]", and a cover of [[the Ronettes]]' "[[I Can Hear Music]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/bluebirds-over-the-mountain-t995513|title =Bluebirds over the Mountain | publisher=Allmusic| accessdate=July 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/risque/tattled/alliwant.asp|title =All I Want to Do| publisher=Barbra and David P. Mikkelson| accessdate=July 12, 2011}}</ref> The diversity of genres have been described as an indicator that the group was trying to establish an updated identity.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 73}} 73]}} The album performed strongly in the UK, reaching number three on the charts. In the US, the album reached a modest 68.

In spring 1968, Dennis began a strained [[Charles Manson#Involvement with Wilson, Melcher, et al.|relationship with musician]] [[Charles Manson]], which persisted for several months afterward. Dennis bought him time at Brian's home studio where recording sessions were attempted while Brian stayed in his room.{{sfn|Guinn|2014|pp=168–70, 340}} Dennis then proposed that Manson be signed to Brother Records. Brian reportedly disliked Charlie, and so a deal was never made.{{sfn|Guinn|2014|p=168}} Without Manson's involvement, the Beach Boys did record one song penned by Manson: "Cease to Exist", rewritten as "[[Never Learn Not to Love]]". The idea of the Beach Boys recording one of his songs reportedly thrilled Manson, and it was released as a Beach Boys single. After accruing a large monetary debt to the group, Dennis deliberately omitted Manson's credit on its release while also altering the song's arrangement and lyrics.{{sfn|Guinn|2014|p=186}} This greatly angered Manson.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=137–48}}{{sfn|Badman|2004|pp=221–23}} Growing fearful, Dennis gradually distanced himself from Manson, [[Manson family|whose family]] had taken over his home.{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=224}} He was eventually convicted for [[Conspiracy (criminal)|murder conspiracy]]; from there on, Dennis was too afraid of the Manson family to ever speak publicly on his relationship, let alone testify against him.{{sfn|Guinn|2014|pp=322–23}}{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=257}}

{{Quote box |align=right |salign = left
|quote=We owe everyone money. And if we don't pick ourselves off our backsides and have a hit record soon, we will be in worse trouble... I've always said, "Be honest with your fans." I don't see why I should lie and say that everything is rosy when it's not.
|source=—Brian Wilson at a 1969 press conference{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=149}} |width  = 25%|}}

On April 12, 1969, the band revisited their 1967 lawsuit against Capitol Records after they alleged an audit undertaken revealed the band were owed over US$2,000,000 (US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|2000000|1969|r=-4}}}} today) for unpaid royalties and production duties.{{sfn|Gaines|1986|p=221}} The band's contract with Capitol Records expired on June 30, 1969, after which Capitol Records deleted the Beach Boys' catalog from print, effectively cutting off their royalty flow.{{sfn|Gaines|1986|p=221}}<ref>{{cite web |title=BBTIMELINE 1969|first=Andrew G. |last=Doe |authorlink=|year=2012 |accessdate=August 14, 2013 |url=http://www.esquarterly.com/bellagio/1969.html}}</ref> In November 1969, Murry Wilson sold [[Sea of Tunes]], the Beach Boys' catalog, to Irving Almo Music, a decision that, according to [[Marilyn Wilson]], devastated Brian.{{sfn|Gaines|1986|p=224–5}} In late 1969, the Beach Boys reactivated their Brother label and signed with [[Reprise Records|Reprise]]. Around this time, the band commenced recording a new album. By the time the Beach Boys tenure ended with Capitol in 1969, they had sold 65 million records worldwide, closing the decade as the most commercially successful American group in popular music.<ref>{{cite magazine| date=November 14, 1970 |title=The Best Kept Secret in the World: "The Most Dynamic Vocal Group Rock Has Produced" |magazine=Billboard Magazine |volume= 82 |issue= 46 |page=4 |publisher= Nielsen Business Media, Inc. |doi= |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=sSkEAAAAMBAJ|page=4}} |accessdate=April 27, 2013}}</ref>

=== ''Sunflower'', ''Surf's Up'', ''So Tough'', and ''Holland'' ===
{{Main|Sunflower (The Beach Boys album)|Surf's Up (album)|Carl and the Passions – "So Tough"|Holland (album)}}
{{BLP sources section|date=May 2014}}
[[File:Beach Boys Good Vibrations from Central Park 1971.jpg|thumb|Performing in [[Central Park]] for a 1971 ABC Television special]]
In 1970, armed with the new Reprise contract, the band appeared rejuvenated, releasing the album ''Sunflower'' to critical acclaim in the UK but indifference in the US.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 73}} 73]}} The album features a strong group presence with significant writing contributions from all band members.{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 73}} 73]}} Brian was active during this period, writing or co-writing seven of the twelve songs on ''Sunflower'' and performing at half of the band's domestic concerts in 1970. ''Sunflower'' reached number 29 in the UK and number 151 in the US, the band's lowest domestic chart showing to that point.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=153–154}} A version of "[[Cottonfields]]" arranged by Al Jardine appeared on European releases of ''Sunflower'' and as a single, reached number one in Australia, Norway, South Africa and Sweden and the top-five in six other countries, including the UK.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}

After ''Sunflower'', the band hired [[Jack Rieley]] as their manager. Under Rieley's management, the group's music began emphasizing political and social awareness.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 155}} 155]}} During this time, Carl Wilson gradually assumed leadership of the band and Rieley contributed lyrics. On August 30, 1971 the band released ''Surf's Up'', named after the Brian Wilson/Van Dyke Parks composition "[[Surf's Up (song)|Surf's Up]]". The album was moderately successful, reaching the US top 30, a marked improvement over their recent releases. While the record charted, the Beach Boys added to their renewed fame by performing a near-sellout set at [[Carnegie Hall]], followed by an appearance with the [[Grateful Dead]] at [[Fillmore East]] on April 27, 1971. The live shows during this era included reworked arrangements of many of the band's previous songs.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=155–8}} A large portion of their [[set list]]s culled from ''Pet Sounds'' and ''Smile'', as author Domenic Priore observes, "They basically played what they could have played at the Monterey Pop Festival in the summer of 1967."{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 140}} 140]}}

[[File:Touring Beach Boys 1972.jpg|thumb|left|225px|upright|(Left to right) [[Carl Wilson]], [[Al Jardine]], [[Ricky Fataar]], [[Dennis Wilson]], [[Blondie Chaplin]] and [[Mike Love]] in 1972]]

{{listen|filename=The Beach Boys "Marcella" sample.ogg|title="Marcella" from ''Carl and the Passions – "So Tough"'' (1972)|description="[[Marcella (song)|Marcella]]" was one of many Beach Boys singles released in this era that achieved wide critical acclaim, but little commercial momentum.| filetype=[[Ogg]]}}

Johnston ended his first stint with the band shortly after ''Surf's Up'''s release, reportedly{{by whom|date=May 2014}} because of friction with Rieley. At Carl's suggestion, the addition of [[Ricky Fataar]] and [[Blondie Chaplin]] in February 1972 led to a dramatic restructuring in the band's sound. The album ''Carl and the Passions – "So Tough"'' was an uncharacteristic mix{{according to whom|date=January 2015}} that included two songs written by Fataar and Chaplin.

For their next project the band, their families, assorted associates and technicians moved to the Netherlands for the summer of 1972. They rented a farmhouse to convert into a makeshift studio where recording sessions for the new project would take place. By the end of their sessions, the band felt they had produced one of their strongest efforts yet.{{according to|date=May 2014}} Reprise, however, felt that the album required a strong single. This resulted in the song "[[Sail On, Sailor]]", a collaboration between Brian Wilson, [[Tandyn Almer]], [[Raymond Louis Kennedy|Ray Kennedy]], Jack Rieley and Van Dyke Parks featuring a soulful lead vocal by Chaplin.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=184, 305}} Reprise subsequently approved and the resulting album, ''[[Holland (album)|Holland]]'', was released early in 1973, peaking at number 37. Brian's musical children story, ''Mount Vernon and Fairway (A Fairy Tale)'', narrated by Rieley and strongly influenced by [[Randy Newman]]'s ''[[Sail Away (Randy Newman album)|Sail Away]]'' (1972), was included as a bonus [[extended play|EP]].{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=181–2}} Despite indifference from Reprise, the band's concert audience started to grow.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}

''[[The Beach Boys in Concert]]'', a double album documenting the 1972 and 1973 US tours, was another top-30 album and became the band's first [[Music recording sales certification|gold record]] under Reprise. During this period the band established itself as one of America's most popular live acts. Chaplin and Fataar helped organize the concerts to obtain a high quality live performance, playing material off ''Surf's Up'', ''Carl and the Passions'' and ''Holland'' and adding songs from their older catalog. This concert arrangement lifted them back into American public prominence. In late 1973, [[41 Original Hits from the Soundtrack of American Graffiti|the 41-song soundtrack]] to ''[[American Graffiti]]'' was released including the band's early songs "Surfin' Safari" and "All Summer Long". The album was a catalyst in creating a wave of nostalgia that reintroduced the Beach Boys into contemporary American consciousness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/readers-poll-the-10-greatest-summer-songs-20130522/6-the-beach-boys-all-summer-long-0368776 |title=Readers' Poll: The 10 Greatest Summer Songs Pictures – 6. The Beach Boys – 'All Summer Long' |publisher=Rolling Stone |accessdate=March 19, 2014}}</ref> In 1974, Capitol Records issued ''[[Endless Summer (The Beach Boys album)|Endless Summer]]'', the band's first major pre-''Pet Sounds'' greatest hits package. The compilation surged to the top of the ''Billboard'' album charts and was the group's first multi-million selling record since "Good Vibrations". It remained on the charts for two years.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=123}} 123]}} Capitol followed with a second compilation, ''[[Spirit of America (The Beach Boys album)|Spirit of America]]'', which also sold well. With these compilations, the Beach Boys became one of the most popular acts in rock, propelling themselves from opening for [[Crosby, Stills, Nash and Young]] to headliners selling out basketball arenas in a matter of weeks.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=193–4}} ''Rolling Stone'' named the Beach Boys the "Band of the Year" for 1974, solely on the basis of their juggernaut touring schedule and material written over a decade earlier.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 194}} 194]}}{{quotation needed|date=May 2014}}

Rieley, who remained in the Netherlands after ''Holland''{{'}}s release, was relieved of his managerial duties in late 1973.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} Chaplin also left in late 1973 after an argument with Steve Love, the band's business manager (and Mike's brother).{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 194}} 194]}} Fataar remained until 1974, when he was offered a chance to join a new group led by future [[Eagles (band)|Eagles]] member [[Joe Walsh]].{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 194}} 194]}} Chaplin's replacement, [[James William Guercio]], started offering the group career advice that resulted in his becoming their new manager.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 194}} 194]}} Under Guercio, the Beach Boys staged a highly successful 1975 joint concert tour with [[Chicago (band)|Chicago]], with each group performing some of the other's songs, including their previous year's collaboration on Chicago's hit "[[Wishing You Were Here]]".{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 194}} 194]}} Beach Boys vocals were also heard on [[Elton John]]'s 1974 hit "[[Don't Let the Sun Go Down on Me]]".{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} Nostalgia had settled into the Beach Boys' hype;{{according to|date=May 2014}} the group had not officially released any new material since 1973's ''Holland''. While their concerts continuously sold out, the stage act slowly changed from a contemporary presentation followed by oldies encores to an entire show made up of mostly pre-1967 music.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 194}} 194]}}

=== ''15 Big Ones'' and ''Love You'' ===
{{Main|15 Big Ones|Love You (The Beach Boys album)}}
{{See also||Adult/Child}}

[[File:The Beach Boys (Logo).png|thumb|right|''[[15 Big Ones]]'' (1976) included a stylized version of the Beach Boys' name by [[Dean Torrence]], which later became their official logo]]

Recorded in the wake of [[California Music]]'s demise, a [[supergroup (music)|supergroup]] that would have involved Brian Wilson, Bruce Johnston, and record producer [[Terry Melcher]],{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 198}} 198]}} ''15 Big Ones'' (1976) marked Brian's return as a major force in the group.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=123}} 123]}} The album included new songs by Brian, as well as cover versions of oldies such as "[[Rock and Roll Music]]", "[[Blueberry Hill (song)|Blueberry Hill]]", and "[[In the Still of the Night (1956 song)|In the Still of the Night]]". "Rock and Roll Music" peaked at number 5 in the US.{{sfn|Warner|1992|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=mTM_9JTeoMIC|page= 330}} 330]}} Brian and Love's "[[It's O.K. (The Beach Boys song)|It's O.K.]]" was in the vein of their early sixties style, and was a moderate hit.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}} The album was publicized by an August 1976 [[NBC]]-TV special, simply titled ''The Beach Boys''. The special, produced by ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (SNL) creator [[Lorne Michaels]], featured appearances by ''SNL'' cast members [[John Belushi]] and [[Dan Aykroyd]].{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 215}} 215]}}

[[File:Brian Wilson 1976 crop.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Brian Wilson behind [[Brother Studios]]' mixing console in 1976]]

The album was generally disliked by fans and critics upon release.{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=364}} During its sessions, Brian's production role was belittled as group members overdubbed and remixed tracks to fight against his desire for a rough, unfinished sound.{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=358}} Carl and Dennis disparaged the album to the press while Brian admitted, "[Undoubtedly] the new album is nothing too deep", but remained hopeful that their next release would be on par with the group's "Good Vibrations".{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=364}}

For the remainder of 1976 to early 1977, Brian spent his time making sporadic public appearances and producing the band's next album ''Love You'' (1977), a quirky collection of 14 songs mostly written, arranged and produced by Brian. Brian revealed to Peter Ames Carlin that ''Love You'' is one of his favorite Beach Boys releases, telling him "That's when it all happened for me. That's where my heart lies."{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 290}} 290]}} ''Love You'' peaked at number 28 in the UK and number 53 in the US and developed a [[cult following]]; regarded as one of the band's best albums by fans and critics alike, and an early work of [[synthpop]].<ref name=RockHallofFame/>

{{Quote box| width=23%|align=right|quote="A diseased bunch of motherfuckers if ever there was one ... But the miracle is that the Beach Boys have made that disease sound like the literal babyflesh pink of health ... Maybe it's just that unprickable and ingenuous wholesomeness that accounts not only for their charm, but for their beauty—a beauty so awesome that listening to them at their best is like being in some vast dream cathedral decorated with a thousand gleaming American pop culture icons."
| source=—[[Lester Bangs]] in a review of ''[[Love You (The Beach Boys album)|Love You]]'' for [[Circus (magazine)|Circus]], June 9, 1977.<ref name="Bangs">{{cite magazine |first=Lester |last=Bangs |title=Feature: ''Beach Boys, The: Beach Boys: The Beach Boys Love You (Reprise)'' |magazine=[[Circus (magazine)|Circus]] |issue=June 9, 1977}}</ref>{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=217–218}}|}}

Referring to "naysayers" of the album, the underground [[fanzine]] ''Scram'' wrote, "Fuck [them] ... [the album showcases] a truly original mix of humor and sadness. The original numbers always dance just a step away from the cliché, dealing with simple lyrical themes that make you wonder why they had never been explored before."{{sfn|Cooper|Smay|2004}} ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' – considering the album in "the same vein" as ''[[Tonight's the Night (Neil Young album)|Tonight's the Night]]'' (1975), ''[[Pussy Cats]]'' (1974), ''[[The Madcap Laughs]]'' (1970), and ''[[Barrett (album)|Barrett]]'' (1970) – described ''Love You'' as: "something almost desperately optimistic ... Wilson sings frayed songs about roller-skating, road-tripping, and [[Johnny Carson]]—like a frazzled man sitting in a corner chanting 'calm blue ocean' over and over. It’s a beautiful, noisy, funny, heartbreaking work of art—one not for everybody, yet vital for anyone who wants to understand Wilson’s overall worldview."<ref name=AVPrimer>{{cite web|last1=Murray|first1=Noel|title=A beginner’s guide to the sweet, stinging nostalgia of The Beach Boys|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/beginners-guide-sweet-stinging-nostalgia-beach-boy-210390|publisher=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=October 16, 2014}}</ref>

After ''Love You'' was released, Brian began to record and assemble ''Adult/Child'', an unreleased effort largely consisting of songs written by Wilson from 1976 and 1977 with select [[big band]] arrangements by Dick Reynolds.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 222}} 222]}} Though publicized as the Beach Boys' next release, ''Adult/Child'' caused tension within the group and was ultimately shelved.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 222}} 222]}} Following this period, his concert appearances with the band gradually diminished and their performances were occasionally erratic.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 226}} 226]}}

== 1978–present ==

{{BLP sources section|date=May 2014}}

=== Internal divisions and personal struggles ===
{{Main|M.I.U. Album|L.A. (Light Album)|Keepin' the Summer Alive}}
{{See also|California Feeling|Merry Christmas from the Beach Boys}}

[[File:The Beach Boys Konzert Michigan 1978 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Performing a concert in 1978]]

The internal wrangling came to a head after a show at [[Central Park]] on September 1, 1977, when the band effectively split into two camps; Dennis and Carl Wilson on one side, Mike Love and Al Jardine on the other with Brian remaining neutral.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=216–217}} Following a confrontation on an airport tarmac, Dennis declared to ''Rolling Stone'' on September 3 that he had left the band: "It was Al Jardine who really knifed me in the heart when he said they didn't need me. That was the clincher. And all I told him was that he couldn't play more than four chords. They kept telling me I had my solo album now [''[[Pacific Ocean Blue]]''], like I should go off in a corner and leave the Beach Boys to them. The album really bothers them. They don't like to admit it's doing so well; they never even acknowledge it in interviews."<ref name=Swenson1977>{{cite magazine|last1=Swenson|first1=John|title=The Beach Boys – No More Fun Fun Fun|magazine=''[[Rolling Stone]]''|date=October 20, 1977|url=http://smileysmile.net/board/index.php?topic=6867.0}}</ref>

The band broke up for two and a half weeks, until a meeting on September 17 at Brian's house. In light of a potential new Caribou Records contract the parties negotiated a settlement resulting in Love gaining control of Brian's vote in the group, allowing Love and Jardine to outvote Carl and Dennis Wilson on any matter.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBTIMELINE |first=Andrew G. |last=Doe |authorlink=|year=2012 |accessdate=October 26, 2012 |url=http://www.esquarterly.com/bellagio/1977.html}}</ref>{{refn|group=nb|Love denied that the group had ever broken up, explaining that, "It was just the end of the tour, Dennis had a lot on his mind, Carl had a lot on his mind. We're working out our thing. Everybody feels a lot calmer now that we've had some time to relax. It was just one of those things that happen over the years between people in the same family."<ref name=Swenson1977/> Dennis maintained to ''Rolling Stone'': "I can assure you that the group broke up and you witnessed it. If there's more to come, then there's more to come."<ref name=Swenson1977/>}}

Dennis withdrew from the group to focus on his second solo album entitled ''[[Dennis Wilson#Bambu|Bambu]]''. The album was shelved just as alcoholism and marital problems overcame all three Wilson brothers.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=124}} 124]}} Carl appeared intoxicated during concerts (especially at appearances for their 1978 Australia tour) and Brian gradually slid back into addiction and an unhealthy lifestyle.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=226–227}} Love remembered: "We were in Australia, and the Wilsons were upset that some of us were not trying heroin with them. That was a division. ... Brian, Carl and Dennis were into one lifestyle, whereas myself and Al Jardine and Bruce Johnston were not."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kerns|first1=William|title=Kerns: Love providing 'Good Vibrations' as original Beach Boy|url=http://lubbockonline.com/filed-online/2016-03-05/kerns-love-providing-good-vibrations-original-beach-boy#.VuTbWlUrJvw|date=March 5, 2016}}</ref>

The Beach Boys' last album for Reprise, ''M.I.U. Album'' (1978), was recorded at [[Maharishi International University]] in Iowa at the suggestion of Love.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 224}} 224]}} Dennis and Carl made limited contributions; the album was mostly produced by Jardine and Ron Altbach, with Brian credited as "executive producer".{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 225}} 225]}} ''M.I.U.'' was largely a contractual obligation to finish out their association with Reprise, who likewise did not promote the result.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 224}} 224]}} The record cemented the divisions in the group. Love and Jardine focused on rock and roll-oriented material while Carl and Dennis chose the progressive focus they had established with the albums ''Carl and the Passions'' and ''Holland''.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

After departing Reprise, the Beach Boys signed with [[Sony Music Entertainment|CBS Records]]. They received a substantial advance and were paid $1 million per album even as CBS deemed their preliminary review of the band's first product, ''L.A. (Light Album)'' as unsatisfactory. Faced with the realization that Brian was unable to contribute, the band recruited Johnston as producer. The result paid off, as "[[Good Timin' (The Beach Boys song)|Good Timin']]" became a top 40 single. The group enjoyed moderate success with a disco reworking of the ''Wild Honey'' song "[[Here Comes the Night]]", followed by their highest charting UK single in nine years: Jardine's "[[Lady Lynda]]" peaked at number 6 in the UK Singles Chart.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} The album was followed in 1980 by ''Keepin' the Summer Alive'', with Johnston once again producing. Barring an appearance on percussion on the closing track, "Endless Harmony", Dennis was absent from this album.

In 1981, Carl quit the group because of unhappiness with the band's nostalgia format and lackluster live performances, subsequently pursuing a solo career.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=124}} 124]}} He returned in May 1982 – after approximately 14 months of being away—on the condition that the group reconsider their rehearsal and touring policies and refrain from "[[Las Vegas]]-type" engagements.{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=373}}

[[Image:Reagans with the Beach Boys.jpg|thumb || The Beach Boys with President [[Ronald Reagan]] and First Lady [[Nancy Reagan]] at the [[White House]], June 12, 1983]]

From 1980 through 1982, the Beach Boys and [[The Grass Roots]] performed [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]] concerts at the [[National Mall]] in Washington, D.C., attracting large crowds.<ref>"July 4: Day of Music, Parades, Fireworks", ''The Washington Post'', Washington, D.C., July 3, 1982, p. D1.</ref><ref name="McCombs">Phil McCombs, "Watt Outlaws Rock Music on Mall for July 4", ''The Washington Post'', Washington, D.C., April 6, 1983, p. A1; <br />Phil McCombs and Richard Harrington, "Watt Sets Off Uproar with Music Ban", ''The Washington Post'', Washington, D.C., April 7, 1983, pp. A1, A17.</ref> However, in April 1983, [[James G. Watt]], President [[Ronald Reagan]]'s [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]], banned Independence Day concerts on the Mall by such groups. Watt said that "rock bands" that had performed on the Mall on Independence Day in 1981 and 1982 had encouraged drug use and alcoholism and had attracted "the wrong element", who would steal from attendees.<ref name="McCombs" /> During the ensuing uproar, which included over 40,000 complaints to the [[Department of the Interior]], the Beach Boys stated that the [[Soviet Union]], which had invited them to perform in Leningrad in 1978, "...obviously ... did not feel that the group attracted the wrong element."<ref name="McCombs" /><ref name=mojo2004>{{cite magazine|last=Holdship|first=Bill|title=The Beach Boys: Mike Love Speaks!|magazine=MOJO magazine|date=December 2004}}</ref> Vice President [[George H. W. Bush]] said of the Beach Boys, "They're my friends and I like their music".<ref name="McCombs" /> Watt later apologized to the band after learning that President Reagan and First Lady [[Nancy Reagan]] were fans.<ref name="Gettysburg">[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=soE0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=AegFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2280,5284705&hl=en Tim Ahern, Associated Press, "Newton concert goes off despite rain", ''Gettysburg Times'', Gettysburg, Pennsylvania, July 5, 1983, p. 7] ''in'' [https://news.google.com/ Google news]. Retrieved February 18, 2010.</ref> White House staff presented Watt with a plaster foot with a hole in it, showing that he had "shot himself in the foot".<ref name="Eagle">[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SdcxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=muMFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3000,2778153&hl=en Associated Press, "Newton Performance Dampened by Rain", ''Reading Eagle'', Reading, Pennsylvania, July 5, 1983, p. 27],''in'' [https://news.google.com/ Google news]. Retrieved February 18, 2010.</ref> The band returned to D.C. for Independence Day in 1984 and performed to a crowd of 750,000 people.<ref>Richard Harrington, "Back to the Beach Boys: Rock Returns to Mall For the Fourth of July; Beach Boys to Perform On the Mall July 4", ''The Washington Post'', Washington, D.C., June 6, 1984, p. B1.</ref>

=== Deaths of Dennis and Carl ===
{{Main|The Beach Boys (album)|Still Cruisin'|Summer in Paradise|Stars and Stripes Vol. 1}}
{{See also|Andy Paley sessions}}

In 1983, Dennis was fired by the group due to his unreliability and bizarre onstage behavior fueled by alcohol abuse. Tensions between Dennis and Love were so high that each obtained a [[restraining order]] against the other.{{sfn|Moskowitz|2015|p=46}} Dennis' alcoholism continued to escalate, and on December 28, 1983, he drowned in [[Marina del Rey]] while diving from a friend's boat trying to recover items he had previously thrown overboard in fits of rage.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 247}} 247]}} Despite his death, the Beach Boys continued as a successful touring act.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 248}} 248]}}

On July 4, 1985, the Beach Boys played to an afternoon crowd of one million in Philadelphia and the same evening they performed for over 750,000 people on the Mall in Washington. They also appeared nine days later at the [[Live Aid]] concert. That year, they released the eponymous album ''The Beach Boys'' and enjoyed a resurgence of interest later in the 1980s, assisted by tributes such as [[David Lee Roth]]'s hit version of "California Girls".{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} "[[Getcha Back]]", released from the album, gave the group a number 26 single in the US. Following this, the group put out "[[Rock 'n' Roll to the Rescue]]" (US, number 68) and a cover of [[the Mamas & the Papas]]' "[[California Dreamin']]" (US, number 57).{{sfn|Warner|1992|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=mTM_9JTeoMIC|page= 330}} 330]}} {{sfn|Warner|1992|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=mTM_9JTeoMIC|page= 330}} 330]}} In 1987, they played with the [[Hip hop music|rap]] group [[The Fat Boys]], performing the song "[[Wipe Out (song)|Wipe Out]]" and filming a [[music video]]. It was a number 12 single in the US.{{sfn|Warner|1992|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=mTM_9JTeoMIC|page= 330}} 330]}} and a number two rank in the UK.<ref>"Beach Boys." Encyclopedia of Popular Music, 4th ed. Ed. Colin Larkin. Oxford Music Online. Oxford University Press. Web. February 23, 2015.</ref>

By 1988, Brian had drifted from the Beach Boys and released his first solo album, ''[[Brian Wilson (album)|Brian Wilson]]'', which received critical acclaim.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} During this period the band unexpectedly claimed their first US number one hit single in 22 years with "[[Kokomo (song)|Kokomo]]", which had appeared in the movie ''[[Cocktail (1988 film)|Cocktail]]'', and soon became the band's largest selling single of all time.<ref>"Beach Boys." Encyclopedia of Popular Music, 4th ed. Ed. Colin Larkin. Oxford Music Online. Oxford University Press. Web. February 20, 2015.</ref> Inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] earlier in the year, the group became the second artist after [[Aretha Franklin]] to hit number one in the US after their induction.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} They released the album ''Still Cruisin'', which went gold in the US and gave them their best chart showing since 1976.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} In 1990, the band gathered several studio musicians and recorded the Melcher-produced title track of the comedy ''[[Problem Child (1990 film)|Problem Child]]''. The album ''[[Summer in Paradise]]'', having no new contributions from Brian because of interference from caretaker [[Eugene Landy]], was released two years later to a poor critical reception, and was a commercial disaster.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}

A lawsuit was filed by Brian in 1989 to reclaim the rights to his songs and the group's publishing company, [[Sea of Tunes]], which he had supposedly signed away to his father Murry in 1969. He successfully argued that he had not been mentally fit to make an informed decision and that his father had potentially forged his signature. While Wilson failed to regain his copyrights, he was awarded $25&nbsp;million for unpaid royalties.<ref>[http://www.beachboys.com/history.html "The Beach Boys – The complete Guide"], ''beachboys.com''</ref> Soon after Wilson won his case, Love discovered that Murry Wilson had not properly credited him as co-writer on 79 Beach Boys songs.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} With Love and Brian unable to determine exactly what Love was properly owed, [[Love v. Wilson|Love sued Brian in 1992]], winning $13&nbsp;million in 1994 for lost royalties. 35 of the group's songs were then amended to credit Love.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1994-12-13/business/fi-8511_1_beach-boys-lead-singer "Company Town : Beach Boys' Mike Love Wins His Case..."] ''Los Angeles Times'' December 13, 1994</ref>

[[File:Don Was - AMA Nashville 2010 - Ron Baker.JPG|thumb|[[Don Was]] produced sessions for [[Andy Paley sessions|a potential Beach Boys reunion album]], but the project was left abandoned{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=283–284}}]]

In 1993, the band appeared in [[Michael Feeney Callan]]'s film ''The Beach Boys Today'', which included in-depth interviews with all members except Brian. Carl confided to Callan that Brian would record again with the band at some point in the near future.{{full citation needed|date=May 2014}} A few [[Andy Paley sessions|Beach Boys sessions devoted to new Brian Wilson compositions]] occurred during the mid-1990s, but they remain largely unreleased, and the album was quickly cancelled because of personal conflicts.<ref name=mojo2004 /><ref>{{cite news|title=Back To The Beach|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,296612,00.html|accessdate=June 30, 2013 |newspaper=Entertainment|date=March 31, 1995}}</ref> In February 1996, the Beach Boys guested with [[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]] on a re-recording of "[[Fun, Fun, Fun]]", which became a British Top-30 hit.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} In June, the group worked with comedian [[Jeff Foxworthy]] on the recording ''Howdy From Maui'', and eventually released ''Stars and Stripes Vol. 1'' in August 1996. The album consisted of country renditions of several Beach Boys hits, performed by popular country artists such as [[Toby Keith]] and [[Willie Nelson]]. Brian, who was in a better mental state at the time, acted as co-producer.

In early 1997, Carl was diagnosed with [[lung cancer]] and brain cancer after years of heavy smoking. Despite his terminal condition, Carl continued to perform with the band on its 1997 summer tour while undergoing chemotherapy. During performances, he sat on a stool and needed oxygen after every song.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|pp=286–287}} However, Carl was able to stand when he played on "[[God Only Knows]]".{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} Carl died on February 6, 1998, two months after the death of the Wilsons' mother, Audree, leaving Brian, Jardine and Love as the three remaining original members.

=== Band split and name conflicts ===
[[File:The Beach Boys concierto.jpg|thumb|left|The touring line-up of Mike Love and Bruce Johnston's "The Beach Boys Band", plus guest member David Marks, in 2008]]
Following Carl's death, the remaining members splintered. Love, Johnston and former guitarist Marks continued to tour without Jardine, initially as "America's Band", but following several cancelled bookings under that name, they sought authorization through Brother Records Inc. (BRI) to tour as "The Beach Boys" and secured the necessary license.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}} In turn, Jardine began to tour regularly with his band dubbed "Beach Boys: Family & Friends" until he ran into legal issues for using the name without license. Meanwhile, Jardine sued Love, claiming that he had been excluded from their concerts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jardine Loses "Beach Boys"|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/jardine-loses-beach-boys-20010803|publisher=Rolling Stone|date=August 3, 2001}}</ref> BRI, through its longtime attorney, Ed McPherson, sued Jardine in Federal Court. Jardine, in turn, counter-claimed against BRI for wrongful termination. BRI ultimately prevailed after several years. Love was allowed to continue to tour as "The Beach Boys", while Jardine was prohibited from touring using any form of the name.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}

Released from Landy's control, Brian Wilson sought different treatments for his illnesses that aided him in his solo career. He toured regularly with his backing band consisting of members of [[Wondermints]] and other LA/Chicago musicians. Marks also maintained a solo career. Their tours remained reliable draws, with Wilson and Jardine both remaining legal members of the Beach Boys organization and BRI.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}} The surviving group members appeared as themselves for the 1998 documentary film ''[[Endless Harmony: The Beach Boys Story]]'', directed by [[Alan Boyd]]. Following the success of 1997's ''[[The Pet Sounds Sessions]]'', many compilations were then issued by Capitol containing new archival material: ''[[Endless Harmony Soundtrack]]'' (1998), ''[[Ultimate Christmas]]'' (1998), and ''[[Hawthorne, CA (album)|Hawthorne, CA]]'' (2001).

In 2004, Wilson recorded and released his solo album ''[[Brian Wilson Presents Smile]]'', a reinterpretation of the ''Smile'' project that he initiated with the Beach Boys thirty-six years earlier. That September, Wilson issued a free CD through the ''[[Daily Mail|Mail On Sunday]]'' that included Beach Boys songs he had recently rerecorded, five of which he co-authored with Love. The 10 track compilation had 2.6 million copies distributed and prompted Love to file a lawsuit in November 2005; he claimed the promotion hurt the sales of the original recordings.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/nov/04/entertainment/et-quick4.4 |title=Mike Love sues Brian Wilson |last1=Lewis |first1=Randy |date=November 4, 2005 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Love's suit was dismissed in 2007 when a judge determined that there were no triable issues.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/may/16/entertainment/et-quick16.1 |title=Beach Boys lawsuit dismissed |last1=Lewis |first1=Randy |date=May 16, 2007 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>

On June 13, 2006, the five surviving Beach Boys (Wilson, Love, Jardine, Johnston, and Marks) appeared together for the celebration of the 40th anniversary of ''Pet Sounds'' and the double-platinum certification of their greatest hits compilation, ''[[Sounds of Summer: The Very Best of The Beach Boys]]'', in a ceremony atop the Capitol Records building in Hollywood. Plaques were awarded for their efforts, with Wilson accepting on behalf of Dennis and Carl. Throughout the year, it was rumored that the band would reform to perform the ''Pet Sounds'' album live in its entirety in November. Ultimately, Wilson began a brief ''Pet Sounds'' tour with Jardine and no other group members.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Doe|first1=Andrew Grayham|title=BBTIMELINE 2006|url=http://www.esquarterly.com/bellagio/2006.html|publisher=Endless Summer Quarterly}}</ref>

==== 50th year reunion celebration ====
{{Main|The Smile Sessions|That's Why God Made the Radio|The Beach Boys 50th Anniversary Reunion Tour}}

[[File:The Beach Boys Smile (7300302550).jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|Reunited in 2012, performing "[[Heroes and Villains]]" in tribute to ''Smile'']]

On October 31, 2011, the Beach Boys released surviving 1960s recordings from ''[[Smile (The Beach Boys album)|Smile]]'' in the form of ''[[The Smile Sessions]]''. The album—even in its incomplete form—garnered universal critical acclaim and experienced popular success, charting in both the Billboard US and UK Top 30. The band was rewarded with glowing reviews, including inclusion in Rolling Stone's Top 500 album list at number 381. ''The Smile Sessions'' went on to win Best Historical Album at the 2013 Grammy Awards.

In February 2011, the Beach Boys released "[[Don't Fight the Sea]]", a charity single to aid the victims of the 2011 Japan earthquake. The single, released on Jardine's 2011 album ''A Postcard From California'' featured Jardine, Wilson, Love and Johnston, with prerecorded vocals by Carl Wilson.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} Rumors then circulated regarding a potential 50th anniversary band reunion.

On December 16, 2011, it was announced that Wilson, Love, Jardine, Johnston and Marks would reunite for a new album and [[Beach Boys 50th Anniversary Reunion Tour|50th anniversary tour in 2012]] to include a performance at the [[New Orleans Jazz Festival]] in April 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/B/Beach_Boys/2011/12/16/19133156.html|title=Beach Boys gear up for reunion |accessdate=December 16, 2011 | work=Sun Media|first=Darryl|last=Sterdan|date=December 16, 2011}}</ref> On February 12, 2012, the Beach Boys performed at the 2012 Grammy Awards, in what was billed as a "special performance" by organizers. It marked the group's first live performance to include Brian since 1996.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/02/08/us-grammys-beachboys-idUSTRE8171QK20120208 | work=Reuters | first=Jill | last=Serjeant | title=Reunited Beach Boys to perform at Grammy Awards | date=February 8, 2012}}</ref> The Beach Boys then appeared at the April 10, 2012, season opener for the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] and performed "Surfer Girl" and "The Star-Spangled Banner". In April, the new album's title was revealed as ''[[That's Why God Made the Radio]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/491809/beach-boys-album-its-all-brand-new |title=Beach Boys Album: 'It's All Brand New' |publisher=Billboard.com |date=September 14, 2009 |accessdate=May 2, 2012}}<br />{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/story/2012-04-23/beach-boys-album/54494556/1 |title=That's where Beach Boys wanna go emdash/ back to the studio – |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=April 23, 2012 |accessdate=May 2, 2012}}</ref> The first single from the album, [[That's Why God Made the Radio (song)|the title track]], made its national radio debut April 25, 2012, on [[ESPN]]'s ''[[Mike & Mike|Mike and Mike in the Morning]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/thebeachboys |title=The Beach Boys |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=May 2, 2012}}<br />{{cite web|url=http://www.cede.ch/de/music-cd/default.cfm |title=portofrei online bestellen – CD DVD Blu-ray Games Bücher Filme Musik MP3 – Schweiz |language=de |publisher=CeDe.ch |date= |accessdate=May 2, 2012}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=August 2014}} and was released on iTunes and other digital platforms on April 26.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sullivan|first=Caitlin|title=Beach Boys Release First New Single in 20 Years|url=http://www.technologytell.com/entertainment/783/beach-boys-release-first-new-single-in-20-years|work=EntertainmentTell|publisher=www.technologytell.com|accessdate=March 2, 2014}}</ref> ''That's Why God Made the Radio'' debuted at number three on US charts, making US chart history by expanding the group's span of [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] top ten albums across 49 years and one week, passing [[the Beatles]] with 47 years of top ten albums.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/beach-boys-beatles-billboard-337926 |title=Beach Boys Surpass the Beatles for Billboard 200 Record |publisher=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=August 14, 2012 |first1=Gary |last1=Trust |date=June 14, 2012}}</ref>

Later in 2012, the group released the ''[[Fifty Big Ones]]'' and ''Greatest Hits'' compilations along with reissues of 12 of their albums. The next year, the group released ''[[Live – The 50th Anniversary Tour]]'' a 41 song, 2-CD set documenting their ''50th Anniversary Tour''. While there were no definite plans, Brian stated that he would like to make another Beach Boys album following the world tour.<ref>{{cite web|first=Ed|last=Condran |url=http://www2.tbo.com/entertainment/entertainment/2012/may/03/7/fxnewso8-golden-boys-ar-399218/?referer=None&shorturl=http%3A%2F%2Ftbo.ly%2FIMf8Fy |title=Beach Boys celebrate 50 years with tour stop in Tampa |publisher=TBO.com |date=May 3, 2012 |accessdate=August 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/brian-wilson-holds-out-hope-for-new-beach-boys-music-20120919 |title=Brian Wilson Holds Out Hope for New Beach Boys Music &#124; Music News |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=September 19, 2012 |accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> In August 2013, the group released ''[[Made in California]]'', a six disc collection featuring more than seven and a half hours of music, including more than 60 previously unreleased tracks,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brianwilson.com/music/ |title=The Beach Boys – Brian Wilson |publisher=Brianwilson.com |accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> and concluding the Beach Boys' 50th anniversary campaign.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}

==== Resumed band split ====

Love reported that on June 1, 2012, he received an e-mail from Wilson's wife and manager [[Melinda Ledbetter]] stating "no more shows for Wilson". Love, who is obligated by his license of the Beach Boys name to maintain revenue flow to Brother Records, then began accepting invitations for when the reunion was over.{{sfn|Love|2016|pp=402–403}} On June 25, Ledbetter sent another e-mail asking to disregard her last message, but by then, Love says, "it was too late. We had booked other concerts, and promoters had begun selling tickets."{{sfn|Love|2016|pp=402–403}} The next day, Love announced additional touring dates that would not feature Wilson. Wilson then denied knowledge of these new dates.<ref>{{cite web|first=Patrick|last=Doyle |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/mike-love-books-beach-boys-shows-without-brian-wilson-20120626 |title=Mike Love Books Beach Boys Shows Without Brian Wilson &#124; Music News |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=June 26, 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=viernes 22 de junio del 2012 |url=http://elcomercio.pe/espectaculos/1431754/noticia-beach-boys-confirmaron-gira-america-sur |title=Los Beach Boys confirmaron gira por América del Sur &#124; El Comercio Perú |publisher=Elcomercio.pe |date=June 22, 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref> Love writes: "I had wanted to send out a joint press release, between Brian and me, formally announcing the end of the reunion tour on September 28. But I couldn’t get Brian’s management team on board (Brian himself doesn’t make those kinds of decisions)."{{sfn|Love|2016|p=404}}

On October 5, Love announced in a self-written press release to the ''LA Times'' that the band would return to its pre-50th Reunion Tour lineup with him and Johnston touring as the Beach Boys without Wilson, Jardine, and Marks:

{{quote|I did not fire Brian Wilson from the Beach Boys. I cannot fire Brian Wilson from the Beach Boys ... I do not have such authority. And even if I did, I would never fire Brian Wilson from the Beach Boys. ... This tour was always envisioned as a limited run ... As the year went on, Brian and Al wanted to keep the 50th anniversary tour going beyond the 75 dates ... However ... we had already set up shows in smaller cities with ... the configuration that had been touring together every year for the last 13 years. Brian and Al would not be joining for these small market dates, as was long agreed upon.<ref name="latimes.com">{{cite news|last=Love |first=Mike |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-mike-love-beach-boys-on-brian-wilson-20121004,0,6311413.story |title=Mike Love sets the record straight on Brian Wilson's 'firing' |publisher=latimes.com |date=October 5, 2012 |accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>}}

Four days later, Wilson and Jardine submitted a written response to the rumors stating: "After Mike booked a couple of shows with Bruce, Al and I were, of course, disappointed. Then there was confusion in some markets when photos of me, Al and David and the 50th reunion band appeared on websites advertising his shows ... I was completely blindsided by his press release ... We hadn't even discussed as a band what we were going to do with all the offers that were coming in for more 50th shows."<ref name="articles.latimes.com">{{cite news|author= |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/oct/09/entertainment/la-et-ms-brian-wilson-al-jardine-respond-to-mike-love-on-beach-boys-flap-20121008 |title=Brian Wilson, Al Jardine respond to Mike Love on Beach Boys flap |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=October 9, 2012 |accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> Love accused Wilson's statements in this press release to be falsified by his agents, again affirming that the presupposed agreements were "well-documented",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jeff|first1=Moehlis|title=Interview: Mike Love|url=http://music-illuminati.com/interview-mike-love/|website=Music Illuminati |accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> and that Wilson had halted further touring dates.<ref name="Dailystar">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/playlist/view/325039/Surf-s-up-again-for-the-Beach-Boys/|title=SURF'S UP AGAIN FOR THE BEACH BOYS|first=Carr |last=Kim |work=dailystar.co.uk|accessdate=July 8, 2012}}</ref> On December 13, Wilson and Jardine played a Christmas show at which they performed the Beach Boys Christmas songs.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qgzoox4asI0 |title=Backstage with Al Jardine |publisher=YouTube |date=December 14, 2012 |accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://smileysmile.net/board/index.php?PHPSESSID=e936cb80c6c4dcc044ac0e893f106c7b&topic=14666.75 |title=Brian & Al KLOS Show 12/13/12 |publisher=Smileysmile.net |accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> Following this appearance, Wilson announced concert dates featuring himself, Jardine and Marks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fraze.com/brian-wilson/ |title=BRIAN WILSON &#124; Fraze Pavilion |publisher=Fraze.com |accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> Love and Johnston continued to perform under the Beach Boys name,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beachboysband.net/TOURSCH/BB_TOUR_SCH.htm |title=The Beach Boys Tour Dates |publisher=Beachboysband.net |date=February 15, 2013 |accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> while Wilson, Jardine, and Marks continued to tour as a trio,<ref>{{cite news|title=Brian Wilson, Al Jardine & David Marks of the Beach Boys to Play Shows as a Trio|url=http://www.rockcellarmagazine.com/2013/03/08/brian-wilson-al-jardine-david-marks-beach-boys-mike-love/|accessdate=March 8, 2013|newspaper=Rock Cellar Magazine|date=March 8, 2013}}</ref> and a subsequent tour with guitarist [[Jeff Beck]] also included former Beach Boy Blondie Chaplin at select dates.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} Reflecting upon the band's reunion in 2013, Love stated: "I had a wonderful experience being in the studio together. Brian has lost none of his ability to structure those melodies and chord progressions, and when we heard us singing together coming back over the speakers it sounded like 1965 again. Touring was more for the fans. ... It was a great experience, it had a term to it, and now everyone's going on with their ways of doing things."<ref name="TheGuardian">{{cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/2013/jul/04/beach-boys-mike-love-interview |title=The Beach Boys' Mike Love: 'There are a lot of fallacies about me' |first=Dave |last=Simpson |work=theguardian.co.uk |accessdate=July 5, 2012 |location=London}}</ref>

Biographer [[Jon Stebbins]] speculated that Love declined to continue working with the group because of the lesser control he had over the touring process, coupled with the lower financial gain, noting: "Night after night after night after night, Mike is making less money getting reminded that Brian is more popular than him. And he has to answer to people instead of calling all the shots himself."<ref>{{cite web|title=Beach Boys Brian Wilson and Al Jardine will radiate the good vibrations in Paso|url=http://www.sanluisobispo.com/2014/09/25/3263164/beach-boys-brian-wilson-and-al.html|publisher=The Tribune|location=California|date=September 25, 2014}}</ref> Writer Stacey Anderson called Love's arguments "wholly unconvincing", facetiously summarizing: "He insists that the larger ensemble with Wilson would have overpowered the modest venues he’d already booked; as anyone can infer, this really means he would have lost money by including Wilson."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Stacey|title=The People vs. Mike Love|url=http://pitchfork.com/thepitch/1296-the-people-vs-mike-love/|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>

[[File:The Beach Boys by Peter Chiapperino.jpg|thumb|right|Love (far left) and Johnston (far right) performing as the Beach Boys in 2014]]

Jardine, Marks, Johnston and Love appeared together at the 2014 Ella Awards Ceremony, where Love was honored for his work as a singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smileysmile.net/board/index.php/topic,17233.0.html |title=Mike receives Ella Award 2014 |publisher=Smileysmile.net |accessdate=March 19, 2014}}</ref> Marks sang "409" in honor of Love, and Jardine performed "Help Me Rhonda". They closed the show with "Fun, Fun, Fun".<ref>{{cite web|last=Riley |first=James |url=http://rockabillynblues.blogspot.com/2014/02/the-society-of-singers-honored-beach.html |title=Rockabilly N Blues Records: The Society Of Singers honored the Beach Boys' Mike Love at the 21st Ella Awards |publisher=Rockabillynblues.blogspot.com |date=February 23, 2014 |accessdate=March 19, 2014}}</ref> Wilson's long time band associate [[Jeff Foskett]] also appeared, but not Wilson. On May 15, 2014 the touring Beach Boys (Love and Johnston) announced a tour celebrating "50 Years of 'Fun Fun Fun{{'"}}, named for [[Fun, Fun, Fun|their 1964 single]]. The tour featured the addition of Foskett, who replaced Mike's son Christian.<ref>{{cite news|last=Blistein|first=Jon|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/beach-boys-plan-tour-to-celebrate-50-years-of-fun-fun-fun-20140515|title=Beach Boys Plan Tour to Celebrate 50 Years of 'Fun Fun Fun'|newspaper=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=May 15, 2014|accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> Foskett left Wilson's band because of encumbering responsibilities, and hopes that Wilson and Love's band would someday converge, believing that the two Beach Boys do not "personally have a problem with each other."<ref>{{cite web|title=Brian Wilson ‘right-hand’ man explains switch to Beach Boys|url=http://www.desertsun.com/story/life/entertainment/music/2014/09/22/beach-boys-brian-wilson-jeffrey-foskett/16070181/|publisher=The Desert Sun|date=September 23, 2014}}</ref> As of September 2014, Jardine has maintained that a continued reunion with the Beach Boys is "really up to him [Love] ... He claims he didn't, that he fired us after the reunion ... He’s a brilliant songwriter, and unfortunately he has brilliant lawyers. We wish him all the best, but doggonit, you know, we’d like to be Beach Boys, too. There you go."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Moehlis|first1=Jeff|title=Interview: Al Jardine|url=http://music-illuminati.com/interview-al-jardine/|publisher=Music Illuminati|date=September 21, 2014}}</ref>

In 2015, ''[[Soundstage (TV series)|Soundstage]]'' aired an episode featuring Wilson performing with Jardine and former Beach Boys Blondie Chaplin and Ricky Fataar at [[The Venetian Las Vegas|The Venetian]] in [[Las Vegas]].<ref name=venetian>{{cite web|title=Brian Wilson And Friends A Soundstage Special Event|url=http://www.venetian.com/entertainment/shows/brian-wilson.html|website=venetian.com|publisher=Venetian|accessdate=November 14, 2014}}</ref> In April 2015, when asked if he was interested in making music with Love again, Wilson replied: "I don’t think so, no,"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caffrey|first1=Dan|title=Eight Minutes with Brian Wilson: An Interview|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/04/interview-brian-wilson/|publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=April 8, 2015}}</ref> later adding in July that he "doesn't talk to the Beach Boys [or] Mike Love."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Harrison|first1=Tom|title=Brian Wilson here with ‘best band I’ve ever worked with’|url=http://www.theprovince.com/travel/Brian+Wilson+here+with+best+band+ever+worked+with/11234184/story.html|publisher=[[The Province]]|date=July 22, 2015}}</ref> On July 25, Love said: "If you get Brian and I, we might go to the piano. But with every band there are cliques that are formed with management, wives, agents, publicists — and the tendency is with some people is they tend to lionize or make one person more important than the others. ... the Beach Boys and all these bands that ever existed are a team. I learned as captain of my cross country team that you don't put a person down to get their best efforts, you encourage them."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Burke|first1=David|title=Keeping Beach Boys sound is a labor of Love|url=http://qctimes.com/entertainment/keeping-beach-boys-sound-is-a-labor-of-love/article_ddd38bef-b86b-593b-a002-dcf7ecf28e80.html|publisher=[[QC Times]]|date=July 25, 2015}}</ref>

== Musical style and development ==
{{See also|Musicianship of Brian Wilson}}
{{Further|The Beach Boys lineups}}

In ''Understanding Rock: Essays in Musical Analysis'', [[music theory|music theorist]] [[Daniel Harrison (music theorist)|Daniel Harrison]] summarizes:

{{quote|Even from their inception, the Beach Boys were an [[experimental music|experimental]] group. They combined, as [[Jim Miller (musician)|Jim Miller]] has put it, "the instrumental sleekness of [[the Ventures]], the lyric sophistication of Chuck Berry, and the vocal expertise of some weird cross between [[the Lettermen]] and [[Frankie Lymon]] and [[the Teenagers]]" with lyrics whos images, idioms, and concerns were drawn from the rarefied world of the middle-class white male southern California teenager. ... [But] it was the profound vocal virtuosity of the group, coupled with the obsessional drive and compositional ambitions of their leader, Brian Wilson, that promised their survival after the eventual breaking of fad fever. ... Comparison to other vocally oriented rock groups, such as [[the Association]], shows the Beach Boys' technique to be far superior, almost embarrassingly so. They were so confident of their ability, and of Brian's skill as a producer to enhance it, that they were unafraid of doing sophisticated, [[a cappella]] glee-club arrangements containing multiple [[suspension (music)|suspensions]], passing [[musical form|formations]], complex chords, and both [[chromatic]] and [[enharmonic]] [[modulation (music)|modulations]].{{sfn|Harrison|1997|p=34}}}}

[[File:The Beach Boys TV.jpg|thumb|The Beach Boys performing in 1964]]

The Beach Boys began as a [[garage band]] playing 1950s style [[rock and roll]],{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 15}} 15]}} reassembling styles of music such as [[surf music|surf]] to include [[vocal jazz]] [[jazz harmony|harmony]], which created their unique sound.{{sfn|MacFarlane|2008|p=36}}{{sfn|Zager|2011|p=216}} In addition, they introduced their signature approach to common genres such as the [[pop ballad]] by applying harmonic or formal twists not native to rock and roll.{{sfn|Harrison|1997|p=35}}  Early on, Love sang lead vocals in the rock-oriented songs, while Carl contributed crisp guitar lines on the group's ballads.{{sfn|Miller|1992|p=194}} Miller observed, "On straight rockers they sang tight harmonies behind Love's lead  ... on ballads, Brian played his [[falsetto]] off against lush, [[jazz]]-tinged voicings, often using (for rock) unorthodox harmonic structures."{{sfn|Miller|1992|p=194}} Harrison adds, "But even the least distinguished of the Beach Boys' early uptempo rock 'n' roll songs show traces of structural complexity at some level; Brian was simply too curious and experimental to leave convention alone."{{sfn|Harrison|1997|p=34}} This new sound was quickly associated with the [[modernism (music)|Modernism]] movement blooming in the Los Angeles music scene.{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 16}} 16]}} Among the distinct elements of the Beach Boys' style were the nasal quality of their singing voices, their use of a falsetto harmony over a driving, locomotive-like melody, and the sudden chiming in of the whole group on a key line.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Davis|first=Jonathan|title=The Influence of the Beatles on the Music of Rock & Roll|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kgoYAAAAMAAJ|publisher=Columbia College, Columbia University|date=1966|journal=King's Crown Essays}}</ref>

During their early years, the Beach Boys released music that displayed an increasing level of sophistication, a period where Brian Wilson consistently acted as the group's primary bandleader, songwriter, producer, and arranger for the group's most commercially and critically successful work.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|pp=105–7}}<ref name="Davis1990"/>  Brian is quoted saying: "Everyone contributed something. Carl kept us hip to the latest tunes, Al taught us his repertoire of folk songs, and Dennis, though he didn't [initially] play anything, added a combustible spark just by his presence."{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} In a 1966 article that asks "Do the Beach Boys rely too much on sound genius Brian?" Carl responded that every member of the group contributes ideas, but admitted that Brian was majorly responsible for their music.{{sfn|Priore|2005}} In 1967, Dennis was cited as "the closest to brother Brian's own musical ideals ... He always emphasises the fusion, in their work, of pop and classical music."<ref name=Rave1967/> An appearance by the band on ''[[Good Morning America]]'' in 1980 was highlighted by journalist [[Ben Ratliff]] who explains: "The clip and everything about it—the occasion for its happening, Dennis's shrug, Al Jardine's silence, Carl's gameness, Brian's self-absorption, Mike Love's critical stewardship of the narrative—seems to say a lot, in seven minutes, about who the Beach Boys are and how they worked together."<ref name="Ratliff2016">{{cite magazine|last1=Ratliff|first1=Ben|authorlink1=Ben Ratliff|title=Looking for the Beach Boys|magazine=[[New York Review of Books]]|date=October 26, 2016|url=http://www.nybooks.com/daily/2016/10/26/looking-for-the-beach-boys-fifty-years-later/}}</ref>

In early 1964, Brian began his breakaway from beach-themed music.{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 28}} 28]}} Later in November of the same year, the group expressed desires to advance from the surf rock style for which they initially became known for.<ref name=Welch1964/> ''New York'' magazine would later refer to the albums ''Pet Sounds'' and ''Smiley Smile'' as their "[[experimental pop]] phase".<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=New York|title=New York |date=1998|volume=31|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=p5MpAQAAIAAJ}}}}</ref> The band went on to incorporate many more [[genres]], from [[baroque pop]] to [[psychedelic rock|psychedelia]] and [[synthpop]].<ref name="AllMusic">{{cite web|title=The Beach Boys Biography on All Music.com|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p3640|pure_url=yes}}|publisher=Allmusic|last=Bush|first=John|accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref>

=== Influences ===
{{Further|List of songs covered by the Beach Boys}}

The band's earliest influences came primarily from the work of [[Chuck Berry]]{{refn|group=nb|"[[Surfin' U.S.A. (song)|Surfin' U.S.A.]]" is a variation of Berry's "[[Sweet Little Sixteen]]".{{sfn|Curtis|1987|p=105}} Under pressure from Berry's publisher, Wilson's father and manager, [[Murry Wilson]], gave the copyright, including Brian Wilson's lyrics, to Arc Music.<ref>Pegg, Bruce. ''Brown Eyed Handsome Man'' (2002): 162–163</ref>}} and [[the Four Freshmen]].{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 16}} 16]}} Performed by the Four Freshmen, "[[Their Hearts Were Full of Spring]]" (1961) was a particular favorite of the group.{{sfn|Harrison|1997|pp=34, 54}} By deconstructing their arrangements of [[pop standards]], Brian educated himself on [[jazz harmony]].{{sfn|Lambert|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=7XsZAQAAIAAJ |page= 5}} 5]}} Taking this into mind, Philip Lambert noted, "If [[Bob Flanigan (singer)|Bob Flanigan]] helped teach Brian how to sing, then [[George Gershwin|Gershwin]], [[Jerome Kern|Kern]], [[Cole Porter|Porter]], and the other members of this pantheon helped him learn how to craft a song."{{sfn|Lambert|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=7XsZAQAAIAAJ |page= 6}} 6]}} Other general influences on the group included [[the Hi-Los]],{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 16}} 16]}}{{refn|group=nb|The Four Freshmen and the Hi-Los which were [[vocal group]]s who appropriated their modern jazz progressions from the trio [[Lambert, Hendricks & Ross]].{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 16}} 16]}}}} [[the Penguins]], [[the Robins]], [[Bill Haley & His Comets]], [[Otis Williams]], [[the Cadets (doo wop)|the Cadets]], [[the Everly Brothers]], [[the Shirelles]], [[the Regents]], and [[the Crystals]].{{sfn|Lambert|2007|pp=14–15}}{{refn|group=nb|In 1967, [[Lou Reed]] of [[the Velvet Underground]] wrote in ''[[Aspen (magazine)|Aspen]]'' that the Beach Boys created a "hybrid sound" out of old rock and the Four Freshmen, explaining that such songs as "[[Let Him Run Wild]]", "[[Don't Worry Baby]]", "[[I Get Around]]", and "[[Fun, Fun, Fun]]" were not unlike "Peppermint Stick" by the Elchords.{{sfn|Unterberger|2009|p=122}} Similarly, [[John Sebastian]] of [[the Lovin' Spoonful]] noted, "Brian had control of this vocal palette of which we had no idea. We had never paid attention to the Four Freshmen or doo-wop combos like [[the Crew Cuts]]. Look what gold he mined out of that."{{sfn|Dillon|2012}} }}

Geoffrey Himes wrote: "Though the Beach Boys are often caricatured as the ultimate white, suburban act, black [[R&B]] was crucial to their sound."<ref name=HimesSurf /> Carl remembers: "Most of [Mike's] classmates were black. He was the only white guy on his track team. He was really immersed in doo-wop and that music and I think he influenced Brian to listen to it. The black artists were so much better in terms of rock records in those days that the white records almost sounded like put-ons."<ref name=HimesSurf /> Their eclectic mix of white and black vocal groups – ranging from the rock and roll of Berry, the jazz harmonies of the Four Freshmen, the pop of [[the Four Preps]], the folk of [[the Kingston Trio]], the R&B of groups like [[the Coasters]] and [[the Five Satins]], and the doo wop of [[Dion and the Belmonts]] – helped contribute to the Beach Boys' uniqueness in American popular music.{{sfn|Murphy|2015|p=58}}

While the Beach Boys are not often associated with [[blues]], Brian has called this a misapprehension, citing [[Smokey Robinson]] and [[Stevie Wonder]] as influences.<ref>{{cite web|title='Head' Games With Brian Wilson|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/67452/head-games-with-brian-wilson|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 8, 2004}}</ref> Regarding surf rock pioneer [[Dick Dale]], Brian clarified that his influence on the group was limited to Carl and his style of guitar playing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaquarian.com/2005/08/10/brian-wilson-interview-with-brian-wilson/|title=Interview with Brian Wilson|publisher=theaquarian.com|accessdate=November 22, 2009}}</ref> Carl himself named Berry, [[the Ventures]], and [[John Walker (musician)|John Walker]] for shaping his guitar style, and that the Beach Boys had learned to play all of the Ventures' songs by ear early in their career.<ref name="Hinsche">{{cite magazine|last1=Hinsche|first1=Billy|authorlink1=Billy Hinsche|title=Carl Wilson Interview|magazine=[[Guitar One]]|url=http://www.billyhinsche.com/story4.html|date=November 2001}}</ref> On [[Jimi Hendrix]] and "heavy" music, Brian said he felt no pressure to go in that direction: "We never got into the heavy musical level trip. We never needed to. It's already been done."<ref name=CoynePart1>{{cite magazine|last1=Coyne|first1=Wayne|authorlink1=Wayne Coyne|title=Playing Both Sides of the Coyne Part One|magazine=Stop Smiling|date=2000|issue=9|url=http://www.stopsmilingonline.com/story_detail.php?id=224}}</ref>

The influence of the Beach Boys' peers combined with Brian's competitive nature drove him to reach higher creative peaks.{{sfn|Zak|2001|p=88}}{{refn|group=nb|The Beach Boys and the Beatles are often stated to have directly reciprocated each other's musical developments during the 1960s. Echoing this, Beatles producer [[George Martin]] said, "No one made a greater impact on the Beatles than Brian [Wilson]."{{sfn|Jones|2008|pp=56–57}} Brian later clarified his side of the matter: "The Beatles ''inspired'' me. They didn't influence me."<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Mettler|first1=Mike|title=Brian Wilson Feels No Pressure When Creating His Sonically Beautiful Pocket Symphonies|magazine=Sound Bard|date=May 13, 2015|url=http://www.soundbard.com/soundbard/brian-wilson-feels-no-pressure-when-creating-his-sonically-beautiful-pocket-symphonies/}}</ref> He identified the main difference between his music approach to theirs is that they simplify songs to their "skeletal form," whereas he would be "impelled to make [them] more complex," and that if he had arranged "[[Norwegian Wood]]", he would have "...orchestrated it, put in background voices, [and] done a thousand things."{{sfn|Fusilli|2005|p=80}} }} Sometime around late 1963, he heard the song "[[Be My Baby]]" (1963) by [[the Ronettes]] for the first time, revamping his creative interests and songwriting.{{sfn|Brown|2008|p=185}} "Be My Baby" is considered the epitome of [[Phil Spector]]'s [[Wall of Sound]] production technique, a recording method that fascinated Wilson for the next several decades.{{sfn|Howard|2004|pp=56–57}} Brian later reflected: "I was unable to really think as a producer up until the time where I really got familiar with Phil Spector's work. That was when I started to design the experience to be a record rather than just a song."{{sfn|Leaf|1978|p=73}}{{refn|group=nb|The Beach Boys recorded cover versions of several songs penned by Spector, including "[[Then I Kissed Her]]", "[[There's No Other (Like My Baby)]]", "[[Chapel of Love]]", "[[Just Once in My Life]]", "[[You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin']]",{{sfn|Lambert|2007|pp=346, 359}} and "[[I Can Hear Music]]".{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=385}}  ''[[The Beach Boys' Christmas Album]]'' (1964) was released as a response to ''[[Phil Spector's Christmas Album]]'' (1963).{{sfn|Lambert|2007|pp=168–169}} }} Other prominent inspirations for Brian included Gershwin's "[[Rhapsody in Blue]]" (1924),{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 10}} 10]}} [[the Beatles]]' ''[[Rubber Soul]]'' (1965),{{sfn|Fusilli|2005|p=80}} and composer [[Burt Bacharach]].{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 64}} 64]}} Brian is quoted: "Burt Bacharach and [[Hal David]] are more like me. They’re also the best pop team – per se – today. As a producer, Bacharach has a very fresh, new approach."{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 64}} 64]}}{{refn|group=nb|The Beach Boys covered "[[My Little Red Book]]" and "[[Walk On By (song)|Walk On By]]" in 1967 and 1968 but left the recordings unreleased.{{sfn|Lambert|2007|pp=284, 352, 354–355}}}}

Experimentation with [[psychotropic]] substances proved pivotal to the group's development as artists.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Griffiths|first1=David|title=Dennis Wilson: "I Live With 17 Girls"|magazine=Record Mirror|date=December 21, 1968}}</ref>{{sfn|Howard|2004|p=58}}{{sfn|Shephard|Leonard|2013|p=182}} In December 1964, Brian was introduced to [[cannabis]] before quickly progressing to [[LSD]] in early 1965. Of his first [[psychedelic experience|acid trip]],{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 65}} 65]}} Brian recalled that the drug had subjected him to "a very religious experience" which enlightened him to indescribable philosophies.{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=136}} The music for "[[California Girls]]" (the first Beach Boys song [[Bruce Johnston]] participated in){{sfn|Hoskyns|2009|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=w7oB2UKVxgQC|page= 105}} 105]}} came from this first LSD experience,{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 65}} 65]}} as did much of the group's subsequent work where they would partake in drug use during recording sessions.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 276}} 276]}}

==== Spirituality ====
[[File:Manuscript of Lyrics for God Only Knows - Rock & Roll Hall of Fame and Museum, Cleveland (by Adam Jones).jpg|150px|thumb|An original handwritten manuscript of the lyrics to "[[God Only Knows]]"]]

The band members often reflected on the spiritual nature of their music (and music in general), particularly for the recording of ''Pet Sounds'' and ''Smile''.{{sfn|Sellars|2015|pp=8–9}} Even though the Wilson family did not grow up in a particularly religious household,{{sfn|DeRogatis|2003|p=35}}{{sfn|Sellars|2015|p=8}} Carl was described as "the most truly religious person I know" by Brian, and Carl was forthcoming about the group's spiritual beliefs stating: "We believe in God as a kind of [[universal consciousness]]. God is love. God is you. God is me. God is everything right here in this room. It's a spiritual concept which inspires a great deal of our music."{{sfn|Priore|2005}} Carl told ''Rave'' magazine in 1967 that the group's influences are of a "religious nature", but not any religion in specific, only "an idea based upon that of Universal Consciousness. ... The spiritual concept of happiness and doing good to others is extremely important to the lyric of our songs, and the religious element of some of the better [[church music]] is also contained within some of our new work."<ref name=Rave1967>{{cite web|last1=Grant|first1=Mike|title='Our influences are of a religious nature': the Beach Boys on Smile|url=http://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/oct/11/beach-boys-smile-brian-wilson|publisher=''[[The Guardian]]''|date=October 11, 2011}}</ref>

Brian is quoted during the ''Smile'' era: "I'm very religious. Not in the sense of churches, going to church; but like the essence of ''all'' religion."{{sfn|Sellars|2015|p=8}} During the recording of ''Pet Sounds'', Brian held [[prayer meeting]]s, later reflecting that "God was with us the whole time we were doing [the] album ... I could feel that feeling in my brain."{{sfn|Fusilli|2005}} In 1966, he explained that he wanted to move into a [[religious music|white spiritual sound]], and predicted that the rest of the music industry would follow suit.{{sfn|Sanchez|2014|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=FC0_AwAAQBAJ|page= 94}} 94]}} In 2011, Brian maintained the spirituality was important to his music, and that he did not follow any particular religion.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yakas|first1=Ben|title=Our Ten Minutes With Beach Boys Legend Brian Wilson|url=http://gothamist.com/2011/10/27/brian_wilson.php|date=October 27, 2011}}</ref>

The Beach Boys included an interpretation of "[[The Lord's Prayer (song)|The Lord's Prayer]]" as the B-side to their 1963 "Little Saint Nick" single.{{sfn|Sanchez|2014|pp=58–59}} Brian expressed apprehensiveness over naming his song "God Only Knows" because, in the 1960s, references to [[God]] in pop music were largely unheard of.{{sfn|Granata|Asher|2003}} Carl said that ''Smile'' was chosen as an album title because of its connection to the group's spiritual beliefs.<ref name=Rave1967/> Brian referred to ''Smile'' as his "teenage symphony to God",{{sfn|Sanchez|2014|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=FC0_AwAAQBAJ|page= 4}} 4]}} composing a [[hymn]], "[[Our Prayer]]", as the album's opening spiritual invocation.{{sfn|Lambert|2007|pp=41, 270}} He spoke of his LSD trips as a "religious experience", and during a session for "Our Prayer", Brian can be heard asking the other Beach Boys: "Do you guys feel any acid yet?".{{sfn|Sanchez|2014|pp=94, 116}} In 1968, Mike Love's interest in [[transcendental meditation]] led the Beach Boys to record the original song "[[Transcendental Meditation (song)|Transcendental Meditation]]".{{sfn|Badman|2004|p=215}}

=== Vocal ability ===
{{Listen
|pos1=right
|filename=Wouldn't It Be Nice vocals.ogg
|title=Vocals of "Wouldn't It Be Nice"
|description=Isolated vocals-only excerpt taken from "[[Wouldn't It Be Nice]]" demonstrating Brian Wilson's lead tenor harmonizing with the other group members.
}}

Brian identified each member individually for their [[vocal range]], once detailing the ranges for Carl, Dennis, Jardine ("[they] progress upwards through G, A, and B"), Love ("can go from bass to the E above middle C"), and himself ("I can take the second D in the [[treble clef]]").<ref name="PopGenius"/>{{refn|group=nb|Starting with the 1970 sessions for the ''Surf's Up'' album, Stephen Desper remembers the emerging corrosive effects of Brian's incessant [[chain smoking]] and [[cocaine]] use: "He could still do falsettos and stuff, but he'd need Carl to help him. Either that or I'd modify the tape speed-wise to make it artificially higher, so it sounded like the old days."{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 160}} 160]}} }} He declared in 1966 that his greatest interest was to expand modern vocal harmony, owing his fascination with voice to the Four Freshmen, which he considered a "groovy sectional sound."<ref name="PopGenius">{{cite magazine|title=Brian Pop Genius!|magazine=Melody Maker|date=May 21, 1966|url=http://i1218.photobucket.com/albums/dd420/kwan_dk/MMMay211966.jpg}}</ref> He added, "The harmonies that we are able to produce give us a uniqueness which is really the only important thing you can put into records – some quality that no one else has got. I love peaks in a song – and enhancing them on the control panel. Most of all, I love the human voice for its own sake."{{sfn|Moorefield|2010|p=17}}<ref name="PopGenius"/> For a period, Brian avoided singing falsetto for the group, saying "I thought people thought I was a [[fairy (gay slang)|fairy]]. ... The band told me, 'If that's the way you sing, don't worry about it.'"<ref name=RCMSharp>{{cite magazine|last1=Sharp|first1=Ken|title=Christmas with Brian Wilson|magazine=[[Record Collector]]|date=January 2006|pages=72–76|location=United Kingdom}}</ref>

Rock critic [[Erik Davis]] wrote, "The 'purity' of tone and genetic proximity that smoothed their voices was almost creepy, pseudo-[[castrato]], [and] a '[[barbershop music|barbershop]]' sound."<ref name="Davis1990">{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Erik|title=Look! Listen! Vibrate! SMILE! The Apollonian Shimmer of the Beach Boys|url=http://www.techgnosis.com/index_beach.html|accessdate=January 14, 2014|newspaper=LA Weekly|date=November 9, 1990}}</ref> According to Brian: "[[Jack Good (producer)|Jack Good]] once told us, 'You sing like [[eunuch]]s in a [[Sistine Chapel]],' which was a pretty good quote."<ref name="PopGenius"/> Writer [[Richard Goldstein (writer born 1944)|Richard Goldstein]] reported that, according to a fellow journalist who asked Brian about the black roots of his music, Brian's response was: "We're white and we sing white." Goldstein added that when he asked where his approach to vocal harmonies had derived from, Wilson answered: "Barbershop."<ref name=GoldsteinSalon>{{cite web|last1=Goldstein|first1=Richard|authorlink=Richard Goldstein (writer born 1944)|title=I got high with the Beach Boys: "If I survive this I promise never to do drugs again"|url=http://www.salon.com/2015/04/26/i_got_high_with_the_beach_boys_if_i_survive_this_i_promise_never_to_do_drugs_again/|publisher=''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]''|date=April 26, 2015}}</ref> On the group's blend, Carl said: "Michael has a beautifully rich, very full-sounding bass voice. Yet his lead singing is real nasal, real punk. Alan’s voice has a bright timbre to it; it really cuts. My voice has a kind of calm sound. We’re big oooh-ers; we love to oooh. It’s a big, full sound, that’s very pleasing to us; it opens up the heart."<ref name=HimesSurf/>

From lowest [[interval (music)|intervals]] to highest, the group's vocal harmony stack usually began with Love or Dennis, followed by Jardine or Carl, and finally Brian on top, according to Jardine,<ref name=Sharp2013>{{cite web|last1=Sharp|first1=Ken|title=Al Jardine of the Beach Boys: Everything You Ever Wanted To Know About "SMiLE" (Interview)|url=http://www.rockcellarmagazine.com/2013/04/02/al-jardine-smile-beach-boys-interview/|website=Rock Cellar Magazine|accessdate=July 2, 2014|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref> while Carl said that the blend was Love on bottom, Carl above, followed by Dennis or Jardine, and then Brian on top.<ref name="HimesSurf">{{cite web|last1=Himes|first1=Geoffrey|title=Surf Music|url=http://teachrock.org/media/essays/surf_himes_with_maia_edits_2.pdf|website=teachrock.org|publisher=Rock and Roll: An American History}}</ref> Jardine explains, "We always sang the same vocal intervals. ... As soon as we heard the chords on the piano we’d figure it out pretty easily. If there was a vocal move [Brian] envisioned, he’d show that particular singer that move. We had somewhat photographic memory as far as the vocal parts were concerned so that [was] never a problem for us."<ref name=Sharp2013/>

Striving for absolute perfection, Brian's intricate vocal arrangements exercised the group's calculated blend of [[intonation (music)|intonation]], [[attack (music)|attack]], [[phrase (music)|phrasing]], and [[musical expression|expression]].{{sfn|Moorefield|2010|pp=17–19}} Sometimes, he would sing each vocal harmony part alone through multi-track tape.{{sfn|Hoskyns|2009|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=w7oB2UKVxgQC|page= 106}} 106]}} [[Jimmy Webb]] has said, "They used very little [[vibrato]] and sing in very straight tones. The voices all lie down beside each other very easily – there's no bumping between them because the pitch is very precise."{{sfn|Hoskyns|2009|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=w7oB2UKVxgQC|page= 65}} 65]}}

=== As instrumentalists ===
[[File:1967 Rickenbacker 360-12 12 string electric guitar owned and photographed by Greg Field.jpg|thumb|150px|right|A [[Rickenbacker 360/12]] identical to the 12-string guitar used by Carl Wilson in the early to mid-1960s]]

The group's instrumental combo initially involved Brian on bass guitar and keyboards, Carl on guitar, and Dennis on drums.{{sfn|Zager|2011|pp=215–16}} Nine months after forming, they acquired national success, and demand for their personal appearance skyrocketed. Biographer James Murphy said, "By most contemporary accounts, they were not a very good live band when they started. ... The Beach Boys learned to play as a band in front of live audiences", but asserted that they eventually became "one of the best and enduring live bands".<ref name=RCMMurphy>{{cite web|last1=Sharp|first1=Ken|title=Catch A Wave: A Chat with Beach Boys Author James B. Murphy|url=http://www.rockcellarmagazine.com/2015/11/06/becoming-the-beach-boys-author-james-b-murphy-interview/|work=[[Rock Cellar Magazine]]}}</ref>

For the recording of the Beach Boys' instrumental tracks, Brian arranged many of his compositions for a conglomerate of [[session musician]]s informally known as [[the Wrecking Crew (music)|the Wrecking Crew]]. Their assistance was needed because of the increasingly complicated nature of the material.{{sfn|Trynka|Bacon|1996|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=HDrIjd5FQ8QC|page= 127}} 127]}}{{refn|group=nb|Many of the musicians and studios Brian used happened to overlap with those used by Phil Spector.{{sfn|Zak|2001|p=88}} }} As a result, a number of songs do not credit the Beach Boys as instrumentalists, but nearly invariably as lead, harmony, or backing vocalists.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} It's the belief of [[Richie Unterberger]] that, "Before session musicians took over most of the parts, the Beach Boys could play respectably gutsy surf rock as a self-contained unit."{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 71}} 71]}}

Carl continued to play beside these musicians whenever he was available to attend sessions.{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 114}} 114]}} In archivist Craig Slowinski's view, "One should not sell short Carl's own contributions; the youngest Wilson had developed as a musician sufficiently to play alongside the horde of high-dollar session pros that big brother was now bringing into the studio. Carl's guitar playing [was] a key ingredient."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tiptopwebsite.com/custommusic2/craigslowinskicom.pdf#page=42 |title= The Beach Boys – The Beach Boys Today! |first= Craig|last=Slowinski|year=2007 |accessdate=October 27, 2012}}</ref>

It is often erroneously stated that Dennis' drumming in the Beach Boys' recordings was filled in exclusively by studio musicians.<ref name=P4K2008>{{cite web|last1=Orme|first1=Mike|title=Pacific Ocean Blue: Legacy Edition|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/11943-pacific-ocean-blue-legacy-edition/|publisher=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=July 8, 2008}}</ref> His drumming is documented on a number of the group's singles, including "I Get Around", "Fun, Fun Fun", and "Don't Worry Baby".<ref name="Slowinski2014">{{cite AV media notes| title = Keep an Eye on Summer 1964 | others= The Beach Boys| year = 2014|first1=Alan|last1=Boyd|first2=Mark|last2=Linette|first3=Craig|last3=Slowinski|authorlink1=Alan Boyd|authorlink2=Mark Linett|publisher=[[Capitol Records]]|type=Digital Liner|url=http://www.thebeachboys.com/#?news=4111}} ([http://fridaynightboys300.blogspot.co.uk/2014/12/the-beach-boys-1964-keep-eye-on-summer.html Mirror])</ref>

=== Songwriting and production ===
{{See also|Brian Wilson's home studio|Brother Studios}}

Brian's experiments with his Wollensak tape recorder provide early examples of his flair for [[exotica]] and unusual percussive patterns and arranging ideas that he would recycle in later prominent work.{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 23}} 23]}} Through attending Phil Spector's sessions sporadically, Brian learned how to act as a producer for records while being educated on the [[Wall of Sound]] process.{{sfn|Moorefield|2010|p=17}} From then on, Brian received some production advice from [[Jan Berry]]. As they collaborated on several hit singles written and produced for other artists, they recorded what would later be regarded the [[California Sound]].{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 24}} 24]}}{{sfn|Howard|2004|p=57}} The positive commercial response to Brian's structurally irregular and harmonically varied pop compositions gave him the prestige, resources, and courage to further his creative aspirations.{{sfn|Harrison|1997|pp=36–37}} He proceeded to explore many unusual combinations of instruments while emphasizing inventive percussion{{refn|group=nb|[[Hi-hat]]s were hardly used on Beach Boys records.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Deevoy|first1=Adrian|title=Beach Boy Brian Wilson: ‘Punk rock? I don’t know what that is’|url=http://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/apr/09/beach-boy-brian-wilson-punk-rock-love-and-mercy|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 9, 2015}}</ref>}} and progressively ambitious lyricism.{{sfn|Harrison|1997|pp=36–38}}{{sfn|Miller|1992|pp=194–95}}

Although he was often dubbed a perfectionist, Brian was an inexperienced musician, and his understanding was mostly self-taught.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|pp=105, 114}} He handled most stages of the group's recording process from the beginning, despite [[Nik Venet]] being credited for producing their early recordings.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=105}} 105]}}{{sfn|Sanchez|2014|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=FC0_AwAAQBAJ|page= 26}} 26]}} At the lyric stage, Brian usually worked with bandmate [[Mike Love]],{{sfn|Carlin|2006|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=eYyovo_AbqAC|page= 73}} 73]}} whose assertive persona provided youthful swagger that contrasted Brian's explorations in romanticism and sensitivity.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=108}} 108]}} Luis Sanchez noted a pattern where Brian would spare surfing imagery when working with collaborators outside of his band's circle, in the examples "[[Lonely Sea]]" and "[[In My Room]]".{{sfn|Sanchez|2014|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=FC0_AwAAQBAJ|page= 27}} 27]}}

==== After 1967 ====

Foreshadowed by ''Beach Boys' Party!'' (1965), much of the group's recordings from 1967 to 1970 displayed sparse instrumentation, a more relaxed ensemble, and a seeming inattention to production quality.{{sfn|Harrison|1997|pp=41, 46}} Brian briefly experimented with ''[[musique concrete]]''{{sfn|Priore|2005|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=81YIAQAAMAAJ |page= 70}} 70]}} and [[minimalist music|minimalist rock]] approaches to music{{sfn|Harrison|1997|p=47}} before retreating to [[Brian Wilson's home studio|his home recording studio]] to record "manic" material in the 1970s, enacting [[syncopation|syncopated exercises]] and [[counterpoint]]s layered on jittery [[eighth note]] [[tone cluster]]s and loping [[Swing (jazz performance style)|shuffle grooves]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Chidester|first=Brian|title=Brian Wilson's Secret Bedroom Tapes|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2014-01-30/music/brian-wilsons-secret-bedroom-tapes/|accessdate=February 1, 2014|newspaper=LA Weekly|date=January 30, 2014}}</ref> During the infancy of Brian's home studio, the group was forced to improvise many technical aspects of recording. In one instance, they used an empty swimming pool as an [[echo chamber]].{{sfn|Preiss|1979}}{{page needed|date=August 2014}}

When Brian abdicated from the group, the other members were forced to take a more active production role.{{sfn|Harrison|1997|p=46}} This is believed to have faltered the quality of their music.{{sfn|Guinn|2014|p=130}} [[Richie Unterberger]] believes that after the December 1967 release of ''Wild Honey'', "the Beach Boys were revealed as a group that, although capable of producing some fine and interesting music, were no longer innovators on the level of the Beatles and other figureheads."{{sfn|Bogdanov|Woodstra|Erlewine|2002|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=1-pH4i3jXvAC|page= 72}} 72]}} The album marked the beginning of Carl's increased role as producer, who described it as "music for Brian to cool out by",{{sfn|Gaines|1986|p=184}} signaling a mellower approach that pervaded into the 1970s.<ref name="Davis1990"/> In 1968, Dennis contributed original songs to ''Friends'', revealing himself as a broodingly soulful songwriter and singer, while Bruce Johnston devised a moody instrumental, "The Nearest Faraway Place",  for ''20/20'' the following year.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=120–21}}

''[[Sunflower (The Beach Boys album)|Sunflower]]'' (1970) marked an end to the experimental songwriting and production phase initiated by ''[[Smiley Smile]]'' (1967).{{sfn|Harrison|1997|p=52}} Of the albums between ''[[Surf's Up (album)|Surf's Up]]'' (1971) and ''Holland'' (1973), Daniel Harrison wrote that they "contain a mixture of middle-of-the-road music entirely consonant with pop style during the early 1970s with a few oddities that proved that the desire to push beyond conventional boundaries was not dead."{{sfn|Harrison|1997|p=52}} While Harrison adamantly states "1974 is the year in which the Beach Boys ceased to be a rock 'n' roll act and became an oldies act,"{{sfn|Harrison|1997|p=52}} ''[[Love You (The Beach Boys album)|Love You]]'' (1977) is perceived by some as an oddity that sounds like no other record in their catalog<ref name="Kempke">{{cite web|last=Kempke|first=D. Erik |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/11669-15-big-oneslove-you/|title=The Beach Boys: 15 Big Ones/Love You : Album Reviews|publisher=Pitchfork|date=August 15, 2000 |accessdate=October 27, 2012}}</ref> with [[synthesizer]]-laden arrangements played almost entirely by Brian.{{sfn|Schinder|2007|p=[{{google books |plainurl=y |id=chj91X0dWzUC|page=124}} 124]}}

== Legacy ==

=== Cultural impact and influence ===
{{Main|Cultural impact of the Beach Boys}}
{{Further|The Beach Boys in popular culture|List of cover versions of Beach Boys songs}}

[[File:Little Deuce Coupe.jpg|thumb|right|The 1932 Ford that appeared on the cover to the platinum certified ''[[Little Deuce Coupe]]'' album]]

Regarded by some critics as one of the greatest American rock groups and an important catalyst in the evolution of popular music, the Beach Boys are one of the most critically acclaimed, [[list of best-selling musical artists|commercially successful]],<ref name=RockHallofFame /><ref name="Rolling Stone">{{cite web|title=100 Greatest Artists: The Beach Boys|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-artists-of-all-time-19691231/the-beach-boys-19691231|publisher=Rolling Stone|last=Buckingham|first=Lindsey|accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref> and widely influential bands of all time.<ref name="Vogue2015"/> The Beach Boys' sales estimates range from 100 to 350 million records worldwide, and have influenced artists spanning many genres and decades.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2306391/Lost-Beach-Boys-lyrics-music-photographs-expected-sell-10m-lying-Florida-storage-unit-years.html|title=Lost treasure trove of Beach Boys lyrics, music and photographs expected to sell for $10m after lying in storage unit for years|date=April 9, 2013|first=Harriet|last=Arkell|work=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=April 13, 2013|location=London}}</ref> The group's early songs made them major pop stars in the United States, the United Kingdom, Australia and other countries, having seven top 10 singles between April 1963 and November 1964.<ref>http://search.proquest.com/docview/444892090/</ref> They were one of the few American bands formed prior to the 1964 [[British Invasion]] to continue their success.{{sfn|Curtis|1987|p=101}} Among artists of the 1960s, they are one of few central figures in the histories of rock.{{sfn|Jones|2008|p=56}}

=== Awards and honors ===
[[Image:Beach Boys Walk of Fame.png|thumb|| The Beach Boys' star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], located at 1500 Vine Street<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/the-beach-boys |title=The Beach Boys &#124; Hollywood Walk of Fame |publisher=Walkoffame.com |date=December 30, 1980 |accessdate=May 22, 2013}}</ref>]]
The group routinely appears in the upper reaches of ranked lists such as "The Top 1000 Albums of All Time."{{sfn|Jones|2008|pp=25–26}} Many of the group's songs and albums including ''The Beach Boys Today!'' (1965), ''Smiley Smile'' (1967), ''Sunflower'' (1970), and ''Surf's Up'' (1971) are featured in several lists devoted to the greatest of all time.<ref name=AcclaimedMusic>{{cite web|title=The Beach Boys|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/The%20Beach%20Boys.htm|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=August 24, 2014}}</ref> The 1966 releases ''Pet Sounds'' and ''Good Vibrations'' frequently rank among the top of critics' lists of the greatest albums and singles of all time.<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/> In 2004, ''Pet Sounds'' was preserved in the [[National Recording Registry]] by the [[Library of Congress]] for being "culturally, historically, and aesthetically significant."<ref name="PetSoundsCongress">{{cite web|title=The National Recording Registry 2004|url=http://www.loc.gov/rr/record/nrpb/registry/nrpb-2004reg.html|publisher=The National Recording Registry}}</ref> Their recordings of "In My Room", "Good Vibrations", "California Girls" and the entire ''Pet Sounds'' album have been inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Home►The Recording Academy►GRAMMY Awards|url=https://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=July 8, 2015}}</ref> On [[Acclaimed Music]], "Good Vibrations" is ranked the third best song of all time, while "[[God Only Knows]]" is ranked twenty-first; the group itself is ranked eleven in its 1000 most recommended artists of all time.<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/>

In 1966 and 1967, reader polls conducted by the UK magazine ''[[NME]]'' crowned the Beach Boys as the world's number one vocal group, ahead of the Beatles and the Rolling Stones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/awards/history/1966 |title=NME Awards History |publisher=Nme.com |accessdate=July 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/awards/history/1967 |title=NME Awards History |publisher=Nme.com |date=May 18, 2013 |accessdate=May 22, 2013}}</ref> In 1974, the Beach Boys were awarded "Band of the Year" by Rolling Stone. On December 30, 1980, the Beach Boys were awarded a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], located at 1500 Vine Street.<ref>[http://www.walkoffame.com/the-beach-boys The Beach Boys| Hollywood Walk of Fame]. Retrieved March 24, 2013.</ref> The group was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in 1988. Ten years later they were selected for the [[Vocal Group Hall of Fame]].<ref name=RockHallofFame/><ref name="vocal hall">[http://www.vocalgroup.org/inductees/beach_boys.htm Vocal Group Hall of Fame Inductees: The Beach Boys], ''vocalgroup.org''. Retrieved January 15, 2007.</ref> In 2001, the group received a [[Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award]]. In 2004, ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the Beach Boys number 12 on its list of the 100 Greatest Artists of All Time.<ref>{{cite web| title = The Immortals: The First Fifty| work=Rolling Stone Issue 946| url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5939214/the_immortals_the_first_fifty}}</ref> Brian Wilson was inducted into the UK Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in November 2006.<ref name="bbc">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/5338196.stm Led Zeppelin make UK Hall of Fame], ''bbc.co.uk''. Retrieved January 15, 2007.</ref>

The Wilsons' California house, where the Wilson brothers grew up and the group began, was demolished in 1986 to make way for [[Interstate 105 (California)|Interstate 105]], the Century Freeway. A [[Beach Boys Historic Landmark]] (California Landmark No.&nbsp;1041 at 3701 West 119th Street), dedicated on May 20, 2005, marks the location.

